{"title_page": "Laila Haglund", "text_new": "{{short description|Archaeologist}}\n{{use dmy dates}}\n{{use Australian English}}\n'''Laila Haglund''' is an archaeologist who played a key role in establishing consulting [[archaeology]] in Australia, and in drafting [[Queensland]]'s first legislation to protect [[Aboriginal Australian|Aboriginal]] cultural heritage. \n\n== Early life and education ==\nHaglund was born in Sweden. She studied [[Latin]], [[ancient Greek|Greek]] and [[Classical Archaeology]] at the [[Lund University|University of Lund]]. During her studies she visited Australia to study Cypriot pottery with Jim and Eve Stewart, where she also met with [[V. Gordon Childe]]. Observations of Aboriginal [[stone tools|lithic]] scatters in the [[Bathurst, New South Wales|Bathurst]] area lead to her switching focus of study to prehistory and conservation at the [[University of London]]. During this period she excavated at archaeological sites in Britain and Sweden. In 1965 she emigrated to Australia with her Australian husband.<ref name=trowel>{{cite web | title=Laila Haglund: The Creation of a Profession | website=TrowelBlazers | date=15 November 2015 | url=https://trowelblazers.com/laila-haglund/ | access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1026657579|title=Deep time dreaming : uncovering ancient Australia|last=Griffiths |first=Billy|publisher=| year=2018| isbn=9781760640446|pages=| oclc=1026657579|isbn=9781760640446|p=13,205}}</ref> \n\n== 1965: Salvage excavation at Broadbeach ==\nIn 1965 Haglund (the only archaeologist in the state at the time<ref name=trowel/>) was asked by the [[University of Queensland]] to conduct salvage excavations on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] at the [[Broadbeach Aboriginal burial ground]]. Six seasons of excavations were undertaken between April 1965 and August 1968, recovering skeletal remains of over 150 Aboriginal people<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/2015/11/8/broadbeach-commemorates-cultural-heritage-and-local-history|title=Broadbeach commemorates cultural heritage and local history - The Queensland Cabinet and Ministerial Directory|website=statements.qld.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref> of the [[Kombumerri clan]].<ref name=trowel/> Excavation methodologies were improvised during the course of the project; the excavation remains one of the largest to have taken place in Australia.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Bowdler|first=S.|last2=Clune|first2=G.|date=2000|title=That shadowy band: the role of women in the development of Australian archaeology|url=|journal=Australian Archaeology|volume=50|pages=27\u201335|via=}}</ref> On the basis of this work Haiglund received a MA from the [[University of Queensland]] and a PhD from [[Stockholm University]]. The excavation report was published in 1976,<ref name=trowel /><ref>{{Cite book|title=An archaeological analysis of the Broadbeach Aboriginal burial ground|last=Haglund|first=Laila|publisher=University of Queensland Press|year=1976|isbn=|location=St. Lucia, Queensland|pages=}}</ref> and described as \"pioneer archaeological research\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McBryde|first=Isabel|date=1977|title=An Archaeological Analysis of the Broadbeach Aboriginal Burial Ground [Book Review]|url=http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=104822817321664;res=IELIND|journal=Aboriginal History|language=EN|volume=1|pages=183}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the excavation, the [[Repatriation and reburial of human remains|human remains were returned]] to the local Aboriginal Community and subsequently reburied in 1988,<ref name=commem>{{cite web | title=Broadbeach commemorates cultural heritage and local history | website=The Queensland Cabinet and Ministerial Directory | date=8 November 2015 | url=http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/2015/11/8/broadbeach-commemorates-cultural-heritage-and-local-history | access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> one of the key examples of repatriation in Australia.<ref name=trowel />\n\n== Cultural heritage legislation work ==\nHaglund drafted the first legislation to protect Aboriginal [[cultural heritage]], which was enacted in 1967<ref name=\":1\" /> as the ''[[Aboriginal Relics Preservation Act 1967]]''.<ref name=hein>{{cite web | title=The Queensland Heritage Act 1992 and the Cultural Record (Landscapes Queensland and Queensland Estate) Act 1987 (QLD): Legislative Discrimination in the Protection of Indigenous Cultural Heritage Commentary Australian Indigenous Law Reporter 1996|first=Henrietta|last=Fourmile|date=1996 | website=Heinonline | url=https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/austindlr1&div=48&id=&page= | access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>  Haglund then sat as a Member of the Advisory Committee to the Queensland Minister for Conservation, Marine, and Aboriginal Affairs from 1967-74. During this period she also lectured at the University of Queensland.<ref name=trowel />\n\n== Professionalisation of archaeology ==\nFollowing the introduction of heritage legislation in [[New South Wales]], Haglund saw the need to professionalise archaeology in Australia.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Gorman|first=A.|date=1992|title=Laila Haglund: progress and professionalisation in consulting archaeology.|url=|journal=Australian Association of Consulting Archaeologists Inc. Newsletter|volume=50|pages=15\u201316|via=}}</ref> She helped establish the [[Australian Association of Consulting Archaeologists]] Inc. (AACAI) and from 1979-1986 she was the inaugural president of the [[Australian Association of Consulting Archaeologists|AACAI]].<ref name=\":2\" /> To mark her major contribution to Australian professional archaeology, AACAI awards, at the annual [[Australian Archaeological Association]] conference, the Laila Haglund Prize for Excellence in Consulting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://australianarchaeologicalassociation.com.au/awards/laila-haglund-prize/|title=Laila Haglund Prize {{!}} Australian Archaeological Association {{!}} AAA|website=australianarchaeologicalassociation.com.au|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> She was the first archaeologist to work purely as a consultant in Australia.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/186508557|title=Digging it up down under : a practical guide to doing archaeology in Australia|last=Smith|first=Claire|last2=Burke|first2=Heather|date=2007|publisher=Springer|others=World Archaeological Congress.|year=|isbn=9780387352633|location=New York|pages=7|oclc=186508557}}</ref>\n==Later career==\n\nHaglund was an adjunct research senior fellow at the University of Queensland in March 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://social-science.uq.edu.au/profile/405/laila-haglund|title=Dr Laila Haglund|date=2018-09-01|website=School of Social Science|language=en|access-date=2019-01-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315050341/https://social-science.uq.edu.au/profile/405/laila-haglund|archive-date=15 March 2019}}</ref> but appears to have retired {{as of|lc=yes|April 2020}}.<ref>Note found on UQ site.</ref>\n== Selected publications ==\n*Haglund, L. 1968. An Aboriginal Burial Ground at Broadbeach, Queensland: Excavation Report. ''Mankind'' 6(12): 676-680.\n*Haglund, L. 1976. Dating aboriginal relics from the contact period. Archaeology in Oceania 11(3): 163-174. https://doi.org/10.1002/j.1834-4453.1976.tb00248.x\n*Haglund, L. 1976. An archaeological analysis of the Broadbeach Aboriginal burial ground. St Lucia, Queensland: University of Queensland Press.\n*Haglund, L. 1984. Checklist and Requirements for Consultant's Reports. Sydney: Australian Association of Consulting Archaeologists Inc.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*{{cite web | title=Laila B. Haglund | website=Australian Association of Consulting Archaeologists | url=https://www.aacai.com.au/membership/profile/94/ }}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haglund, Laila}}\n[[Category:Australian archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Stockholm University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Archaeologist}}\n{{use dmy dates}}\n{{use Australian English}}\n'''Laila Haglund''' is an archaeologist who played a key role in establishing consulting [[archaeology]] in Australia, and in drafting [[Queensland]]'s first legislation to protect [[Aboriginal Australian|Aboriginal]] cultural heritage. \n\n== Early life and education ==\nHaglund was born in Sweden. She studied [[Latin]], [[ancient Greek|Greek]] and [[Classical Archaeology]] at the [[Lund University|University of Lund]]. During her studies she visited Australia to study Cypriot pottery with Jim and Eve Stewart, where she also met with [[V. Gordon Childe]]. Observations of Aboriginal [[stone tools|lithic]] scatters in the [[Bathurst, New South Wales|Bathurst]] area lead to her switching focus of study to prehistory and conservation at the [[University of London]]. During this period she excavated at archaeological sites in Britain and Sweden. In 1965 she emigrated to Australia with her Australian husband.<ref name=trowel>{{cite web | title=Laila Haglund: The Creation of a Profession | website=TrowelBlazers | date=15 November 2015 | url=https://trowelblazers.com/laila-haglund/ | access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref></ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1026657579|title=Deep time dreaming : uncovering ancient Australia|last=Griffiths |first=Billy|publisher=| year=2018| isbn=9781760640446|pages=| oclc=1026657579|isbn=9781760640446|p=13,205}}</ref> \n\n== 1965: Salvage excavation at Broadbeach ==\nIn 1965 Haglund (the only archaeologist in the state at the time<ref name=trowel/>) was asked by the [[University of Queensland]] to conduct salvage excavations on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] at the [[Broadbeach Aboriginal burial ground]]. Six seasons of excavations were undertaken between April 1965 and August 1968, recovering skeletal remains of over 150 Aboriginal people<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/2015/11/8/broadbeach-commemorates-cultural-heritage-and-local-history|title=Broadbeach commemorates cultural heritage and local history - The Queensland Cabinet and Ministerial Directory|website=statements.qld.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref> of the [[Kombumerri clan]].<ref name=trowel/> Excavation methodologies were improvised during the course of the project; the excavation remains one of the largest to have taken place in Australia.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Bowdler|first=S.|last2=Clune|first2=G.|date=2000|title=That shadowy band: the role of women in the development of Australian archaeology|url=|journal=Australian Archaeology|volume=50|pages=27\u201335|via=}}</ref> On the basis of this work Haiglund received a MA from the [[University of Queensland]] and a PhD from [[Stockholm University]]. The excavation report was published in 1976,<ref name=trowel /><ref>{{Cite book|title=An archaeological analysis of the Broadbeach Aboriginal burial ground|last=Haglund|first=Laila|publisher=University of Queensland Press|year=1976|isbn=|location=St. Lucia, Queensland|pages=}}</ref> and described as \"pioneer archaeological research\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McBryde|first=Isabel|date=1977|title=An Archaeological Analysis of the Broadbeach Aboriginal Burial Ground [Book Review]|url=http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=104822817321664;res=IELIND|journal=Aboriginal History|language=EN|volume=1|pages=183}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the excavation, the [[Repatriation and reburial of human remains|human remains were returned]] to the local Aboriginal Community and subsequently reburied in 1988,<ref name=commem>{{cite web | title=Broadbeach commemorates cultural heritage and local history | website=The Queensland Cabinet and Ministerial Directory | date=8 November 2015 | url=http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/2015/11/8/broadbeach-commemorates-cultural-heritage-and-local-history | access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> one of the key examples of repatriation in Australia.<ref name=trowel />\n\n== Cultural heritage legislation work ==\nHaglund drafted the first legislation to protect Aboriginal [[cultural heritage]], which was enacted in 1967<ref name=\":1\" /> as the ''[[Aboriginal Relics Preservation Act 1967]]''.<ref name=hein>{{cite web | title=The Queensland Heritage Act 1992 and the Cultural Record (Landscapes Queensland and Queensland Estate) Act 1987 (QLD): Legislative Discrimination in the Protection of Indigenous Cultural Heritage Commentary Australian Indigenous Law Reporter 1996|first=Henrietta|last=Fourmile|date=1996 | website=Heinonline | url=https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/austindlr1&div=48&id=&page= | access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>  Haglund then sat as a Member of the Advisory Committee to the Queensland Minister for Conservation, Marine, and Aboriginal Affairs from 1967-74. During this period she also lectured at the University of Queensland.<ref name=trowel />\n\n== Professionalisation of archaeology ==\nFollowing the introduction of heritage legislation in [[New South Wales]], Haglund saw the need to professionalise archaeology in Australia.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Gorman|first=A.|date=1992|title=Laila Haglund: progress and professionalisation in consulting archaeology.|url=|journal=Australian Association of Consulting Archaeologists Inc. Newsletter|volume=50|pages=15\u201316|via=}}</ref> She helped establish the [[Australian Association of Consulting Archaeologists]] Inc. (AACAI) and from 1979-1986 she was the inaugural president of the [[Australian Association of Consulting Archaeologists|AACAI]].<ref name=\":2\" /> To mark her major contribution to Australian professional archaeology, AACAI awards, at the annual [[Australian Archaeological Association]] conference, the Laila Haglund Prize for Excellence in Consulting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://australianarchaeologicalassociation.com.au/awards/laila-haglund-prize/|title=Laila Haglund Prize {{!}} Australian Archaeological Association {{!}} AAA|website=australianarchaeologicalassociation.com.au|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> She was the first archaeologist to work purely as a consultant in Australia.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/186508557|title=Digging it up down under : a practical guide to doing archaeology in Australia|last=Smith|first=Claire|last2=Burke|first2=Heather|date=2007|publisher=Springer|others=World Archaeological Congress.|year=|isbn=9780387352633|location=New York|pages=7|oclc=186508557}}</ref>\n==Later career==\n\nHaglund was an adjunct research senior fellow at the University of Queensland in March 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://social-science.uq.edu.au/profile/405/laila-haglund|title=Dr Laila Haglund|date=2018-09-01|website=School of Social Science|language=en|access-date=2019-01-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315050341/https://social-science.uq.edu.au/profile/405/laila-haglund|archive-date=15 March 2019}}</ref> but appears to have retired {{as of|lc=yes|April 2020}}.<ref>Note found on UQ site.</ref>\n== Selected publications ==\n*Haglund, L. 1968. An Aboriginal Burial Ground at Broadbeach, Queensland: Excavation Report. ''Mankind'' 6(12): 676-680.\n*Haglund, L. 1976. Dating aboriginal relics from the contact period. Archaeology in Oceania 11(3): 163-174. https://doi.org/10.1002/j.1834-4453.1976.tb00248.x\n*Haglund, L. 1976. An archaeological analysis of the Broadbeach Aboriginal burial ground. St Lucia, Queensland: University of Queensland Press.\n*Haglund, L. 1984. Checklist and Requirements for Consultant's Reports. Sydney: Australian Association of Consulting Archaeologists Inc.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*{{cite web | title=Laila B. Haglund | website=Australian Association of Consulting Archaeologists | url=https://www.aacai.com.au/membership/profile/94/ }}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haglund, Laila}}\n[[Category:Australian archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Stockholm University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Laterthanyouthink", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copyedit (minor)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laila_Haglund"}
{"title_page": "Madhukar Parekh", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Madhukar Parekh\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_upright      = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Madhukar Balvantray Parekh\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1946}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai]], India\n| residence          = Mumbai, India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| other_names        = M. B. Parekh\n| education          = B.Sc. [[Institute of Chemical Technology]], M.Sc. [[University of Wisconsin]]\n| occupation         = Chairman [[Pidilite Industries]]\n| net_worth          = {{USD|link=yes|7.5}} billion (February 2020)<ref>{{cite web |title=Madhukar Parekh & family |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/madhukar-parekh/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=18 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n| father             = [[Balvant Parekh]]\n}}\n\n'''Madhukar Balvantray Parekh''' is an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[entrepreneur]], Chairman of [[Pidilite Industries]], a global company among the leaders in adhesives and sealants, construction chemicals, hobby colors.<ref>{{cite news|title=Madhukar Parekh's Pidilite Industries Earns His Family $1.36 Billion|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2012/10/24/madhukar-parekhs-pidilite-industries-earns-his-family-1-36-billion/|accessdate=2 March 2015|publisher=Forbes}}</ref> Madhukar is 16th richest Indian with a net worth of US$7.5 billion as of 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/india-billionaires/list/#tab:overall|title=India\u2019s Richest List - Madhukar Parekh|last=|first=|date=|work=|accessdate=23 June 2019|publisher=Forbes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Best Global Brands 2014|url=http://www.brandchannel.com/features_profile.asp?pr_id=369|accessdate=2 March 2015|publisher=Brand Channel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402133045/http://www.brandchannel.com/features_profile.asp?pr_id=369|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nMadhukar born in the family of Banvantray Kalyanji Parekh in [[Jain]] Family in [[Mumbai]] India. Madhukar completed Bachelor of Science in Engineering from the [[University department of chemical technology|University Department of Chemical Technology]] of [[University of Mumbai]] and Masters in Chemical engineering from [[University of Wisconsin]] United States in 1969. Madhukar joined [[Abbot Laboratories]] USA after his [[masters degree]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Madhukar Parekh Of Pidilite Is Moving From Strength To Strength|url=http://forbesindia.com/article/india-rich-list-2014/madhukar-parekh-of-pidilite-is-moving-from-strength-to-strength/38917/0|accessdate=2 March 2015|publisher=Forbes}}</ref>\n\nMadhukar Joined his father's business [[Pidilite Industries]] in 1971<ref>{{cite news|title=Can Pidilite Keep Blowing Its Trumpet?|url=http://www.outlookbusiness.com/article_v3.aspx?artid=287920|accessdate=2 March 2015|publisher=Outlook Business}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A tale of sticky success|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-brandline/a-tale-of-sticky-success/article1010770.ece|accessdate=2 March 2015|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n==Awards & Recognitions==\n* 1. Ranked 13 on Business Today Top 25 business leaders in India 2012<ref>{{cite news|title=Long distance champs|url=http://businesstoday.intoday.in/story/indias-best-ceos-the-other-nineteen-in-the-list/1/21689.html|accessdate=2 March 2015|publisher=Business Today}}</ref>\n* 2. Chemtech Business leader of the Year 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Leadership & Excellence Awards|url=http://www.pidilite.com/award-content.php?&req=1&KeepThis=true&TB_iframe=true&width=780|website=www.pidilite.com|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref>\n* 3. Ranked  34 on Forbes India Richest list 2014\n* 3. EY  Entrepreneur of the year - Consumer products 2014<ref>{{cite news|title=The winners of the Entrepreneur Of The Year 2014 awards|url=http://www.ey.com/IN/en/About-us/Entrepreneurship/Entrepreneur-Of-The-Year/EY-eoy-2014-india-winners|accessdate=2 March 2015|publisher=EY}}</ref>\n\n==Associations==\nMadhukar serves as the chairman and managing director of Vinyl Chemicals India Limited, an Independent non executive director of Excel Industries Limited . Madhukar also serves as an Executive Director of [[Pidilite Industries]] and Vinyl Chemicals India Ltd.<ref>{{cite news|title=Madhukar Balvantray Parekh|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=8695513&ticker=878761|accessdate=2 March 2015|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nMadhukar is married, have two children and lives in [[Mumbai]] India\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parekh, Madhukar}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian billionaires]]\n[[Category:University of Mumbai alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian industrialists]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin&ndash;Madison alumni]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Madhukar Parekh\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_upright      = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Madhukar Balvantray Parekh\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1946}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai]], India\n| residence          = Mumbai, India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| other_names        = M. B. Parekh\n| education          = B.Sc. [[Institute of Chemical Technology]], M.Sc. [[University of Wisconsin]]\n| occupation         = Chairman [[Pidilite Industries]]\n| net_worth          = {{USD|link=yes|7.5}} billion (February 2020)<ref>{{cite web |title=Madhukar Parekh & family |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/madhukar-parekh/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=