{"title_page": "Kate Silverton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kate Silverton\n| image              = Geneva International Motor Show 2018, Le Grand-Saconnex (1X7A0488).jpg\n| caption            = \n| birthname          = Kate Silverton\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = [[Waltham Abbey (town)|Waltham Abbey]], [[Essex]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = [[University of Durham]]\n| occupation         = [[Journalist]], [[News presenter|broadcaster]], [[news presenter|newsreader]]\n| years_active       = 1992\u2013present\n| alias              = \n| title              = \n| family             = \n| spouse             = {{marriage| Mike Heron|18 December 2010}}\n| domesticpartner    = \n| children           = 2\n| relatives          = \n| nationality        = [[British people|British]]\n| religion           = \n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| credits            = ''[[BBC Breakfast]]''<br>''[[BBC News at Six]]''<br>''[[BBC News at Ten]]''<br>''[[BBC News Summary]]''<br>''[[BBC Weekend News]]''<br>''[[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC News Channel]]''<br>''[[BBC World News]]''<br>''[[GMT (TV series)|GMT]]''\n| agent              = \n| URL                = \n}}\n'''Kate Silverton''' is an English journalist and broadcaster working for the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Newsroom spat forces BBC anchor to quit |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1499234/Newsroom-spat-forces-BBC-anchor-to-quit.html |accessdate=1 February 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=26 September 2005}}</ref> Generally a main and relief presenter for the BBC, Silverton can be seen regularly presenting the ''[[BBC News at One]]'', ''[[BBC News at Six]]'', ''[[BBC News at Ten]]'', and ''[[BBC Weekend News]]'', and is the current Deputy Presenter of the ''[[BBC News at One]]'' as well as making occasional appearances on the [[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC News Channel]] and [[BBC World News]]. In 2018 she participated in the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 16)|sixteenth series]] of BBC's ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'', paired with professional dancer [[Aljaz Skorjanec]] finishing in 8th place. \n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nSilverton was born in [[Waltham Abbey (town)|Waltham Abbey]] in [[Essex]], England, the daughter of Terry Silverton, a [[Hackney carriage|black-cab driver]]-turned-registered [[hypnotherapy|hypnotherapist]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/5292044/Kate-Silverton-now-its-her-turn-to-make-the-news.html |title=Kate Silverton: now it's her turn to make the news |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=8 May 2009 |accessdate=27 September 2010 |location=London |first=Celia |last=Walden}}</ref> and Patricia Silverton. Silverton has two sisters, Claire and Amy. Silverton attended [[West Hatch High School]] in [[Chigwell]], Essex, where she was a junior swimming champion. She also competed in the [[triathlon]].<ref name=\"Webster\">{{cite news |last=Webster |first=Nick |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=16202006&method=full&siteid=94762&headline=attractive--ambitious-and-very-scary--tv-newsreader-kate-silverton-is-the---kaplinsky-klone--name_page.html |title=Attractive, ambitious and very scary |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=3 October 2005 |accessdate=27 September 2010}}</ref> She was a [[Girl Guide]] and gained the [[Queen's Guide (Girlguiding UK)|Queen's Guide Award]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Centenary of Guiding |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/womanshour/01/2009_35_mon.shtml |work=Woman's Hour |publisher=BBC Radio 4 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nSilverton graduated from [[St. Cuthbert's Society]], a college at [[Durham University]] with a Bachelor of Science degree in [[Psychology]], having previously studied Arabic and Middle Eastern history for a year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bigcat/presenters/katesilverton/ |title=Kate Silverton joins the Big Cat team |work=BBC |accessdate=27 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Early career ===\nSilverton worked for a London-based bank before becoming a journalist. She trained with the [[BBC]], working on ''[[BBC Look North (North East and Cumbria)|Look North]]'' news before becoming a reporter and presenter at [[ITV Tyne Tees|Tyne Tees Television]].\n\nShe was a panellist on [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]'s ''[[The Wright Stuff]]''. She also featured on ''[[The Heaven and Earth Show]]'', ''Big Strong Boys'',<ref>{{cite news |last=Jury |first=Louise |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/viewers-put-off-their-breakfast-by-bbc-presenters-psychedelic-blouse-480769.html |title=Viewers put off their breakfast by BBC presenter's psychedelic blouse |newspaper=The Independent |date=2 June 2006 |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> and ''Weekend Breakfast'' on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], before joining [[BBC News]].\n\nIn 2003, Silverton allegedly hit [[Rod Liddle]], the former editor of [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme, during a pilot for a new political show. Liddle said: \"I made a stupid comment about the disabled which Kate rightly took exception to.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news |last=Macgregor |first=Fiona |url=http://news.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=474&id=1999392005 |date=27 September 2005|title=Here is the news ... I cannot work with that woman, so I quit |newspaper=Scotland on Sunday |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===BBC News===\n{{main|BBC News}}\nFrom 2005 until December 2007, Silverton was a presenter on [[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC News 24]] and also a regular relief presenter for ''[[BBC Breakfast]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}}\n\nIn December 2007, she was named as the presenter of the ''BBC News 8 p.m. summary'', a 90-second round-up of the news shown on [[BBC One]], which she presented for two months. She presented the ''[[BBC News at One]]'' from February to August 2008, whilst main presenter [[Sophie Raworth]] was on maternity leave.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.katesilverton.com |title=Kate Silverton to present news bulletin - Silverton's official website |publisher=Katesilverton.com |accessdate=27 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, Silverton revealed in an interview in ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper that she had been offered a main presenter role for the relaunch of [[5 News]] in 2007 which she declined.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n[[BBC Scotland]] apologised to viewers in August 2010, after Silverton swore at the end of a news bulletin on live television. Viewers in Scotland were the only ones who heard the words. A spokesman for BBC Scotland said: \"Kate thought she was off-air at the time. The microphones hadn't been faded down and the mistake only went out in Scotland.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Stephen |title=BBC presenter Kate Silverton's 'bloody' big gaffe - heard only in Scotland |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/bbc-presenter-kate-silvertons-bloody-1067200 |accessdate=19 November 2013 |date=15 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nSilverton took maternity leave in October 2011, and returned to the ''News at One'' in April 2012. Until May 2012, she was the deputy presenter of the BBC ''News at One'',<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/biographies/biogs/news/katesilverton.shtml Kate Silverton] - BBC Press Office profile</ref> presenting on Mondays and when main presenter Sophie Raworth was unavailable. [[Sian Williams]] later took over this role. Silverton returned to the deputy role in October 2013 to cover for Williams' leave. However, Williams later left the BBC so Silverton regained her role.\n\nSilverton returned to the BBC News in July 2015 after maternity leave, and was seconded to BBC Radio 4. She returned from her secondment in April 2016.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\n=== Other BBC projects ===\nOn 1 April 2008, alongside the [[historian]] [[Dan Snow]], she presented live coverage of the celebrations held at [[RAF Fairford]] for the 90th Birthday of the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref>{{cite news |title=DOCUMENTARY: Royal Air Force: Celebrating 90 Years |url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/52048/DOCUMENTARY-Royal-Air-Force-Celebrating-90-Years-2-15pm-BBC1 |accessdate=28 October 2013 |newspaper=Daily Express |date=11 July 2008}}</ref> In 2008, Silverton joined the presenting team for ''[[Big Cat Diary]]'' on [[BBC One]].<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC: Big Cat Live 2008 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bigcat/about/|work=BBC|accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> She co-presented coverage of ''[[New Year Live]]'' aboard {{HMS|Belfast|C35|6}} in London on 31 December 2008 on BBC One with [[Nick Knowles]].<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC One: New Year Live |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00gd5cn |work=BBC |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, she appeared as a mentor in the [[BBC Two]] series ''[[The Speaker]]'', offering her advice on good storytelling and public speaking.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC: The Speaker |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/speaker/improve/storytelling/ |work=BBC |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, she presented a documentary called ''10 Things You Need to Know About Sleep'', which looked at different ways to deal with [[insomnia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=BBC One - 10 Things You Need to Know About Sleep |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00j08h7 |work=BBC |accessdate=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010, she presented the Sunday morning show on BBC Radio 5 Live, running from 09:30 to 11:00.<ref>{{cite web |title=Radio 5 Live's new-look weekend line-up revealed |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/09_september/03/5live.shtml |work=BBC Press Office |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Silverton interviewed [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]], who called for a halt to the killing of rhinos for their horns in Africa.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince William hits out at rhino poachers |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18489579 |work=BBC News |date=19 June 2012 |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> Silverton has also acted as a stand-in presenter for the [[Radio Four]] series ''[[Last Word]]''.\n\n===''Strictly Come Dancing'' ===\nBetween 8 September and 18 November 2018, Silverton participated in the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 16)|sixteenth series]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0bk1pbm |title=BBC One - Strictly Come Dancing, Series 16, Launch |publisher=BBC One |date=September 8, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018}}</ref> with professional dance partner [[Alja\u017e Skorjanec]]. The couple were eliminated in Week 9 (Blackpool), losing a dance-off against [[Graeme Swann]] and his partner [[Oti Mabuse]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n|- style=\"text-align:Center; background:#ccc;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Week # \n! rowspan=\"2\" | Dance / Song \n! colspan=\"5\" | Judges' score \n! rowspan=\"2\" | Result \n|- style=\"text-align:center; background:#ccc;\"\n| style=\"width:10%; \" |Revel Horwood\n| style=\"width:10%; \" |Bussell\n| style=\"width:10%; \" |Ballas\n| style=\"width:10%; \" |Tonioli\n| style=\"width:10%; \" |'''Total'''\n|- style=\"text-align: center; background:#faf6f6;\"\n|1\n|[[Cha-cha-cha (dance)|Cha-cha-cha]] / \"[[Kiss (Prince song)|Kiss]]\"\n|4\n|6\n|4\n|6\n|20\n|No Elimination\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|2\n|[[Tango]] / \"[[No Roots (song)|No Roots]]\" \n|6\n|7\n|7\n|7\n|27\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|3\n|[[Foxtrot]] / \"[[Why Don't You Do Right?]]\"\n|6\n|7\n|8\n|8\n|29\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|4\n|[[Samba]] / \"[[Africa (Toto song)|Africa]]\"\n|4\n|5\n|5\n|6\n|20\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\n|5\n|[[Viennese waltz]] / \"Finally Mine\"\n|6\n|6\n|6\n|8{{ref|A|A}}\n|26\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|6\n|[[Rhumba]] / \"[[Skin (Rag'n'Bone Man song)|Skin]]\"\n|4\n|6\n|5\n|5\n|<span style=\"color:red\">''20''</span>\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|7\n|[[Argentine tango]] / \"Assassin's Tango\"\n|4\n|6\n|6\n|7\n|23\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|8\n|[[Quickstep]] / \"[[I Want You to Want Me]]\"\n|7\n|7\n|8\n|8\n|30\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|9\n|[[American Smooth]] / \"[[Everlasting Love]]\"\n|7\n|7\n|8\n|8\n|30\n|Eliminated\n|}\n;Notes\n;*<small><span style=\"color:red\">'''Red'''</span> number indicates Kate & Alja\u017e were at the bottom of the leaderboard</small>\n:{{note|A|A}} [[Alfonso Ribeiro]] filled in for Tonioli\n\n== Philip Hayton incident ==\nIn September 2005, Silverton drew media attention when her BBC News 24 co-newsreader [[Philip Hayton]], who had worked for the BBC for 37 years, resigned his position six months into a year's contract, citing issues of \"incompatibility\" with Silverton.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC newsreader quits over 'clash' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4283824.stm |accessdate=29 October 2013 |work=BBC News |date=26 September 2005}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', without substantiation and quoting an unnamed 'insider', reported that Hayton turned to Silverton during a break and said \"I don't like you\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news |last=Alleyne |first=Richard |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1499354/Chemistry-as-Silverton-clicks-with-new-partner.html |title=Chemistry as Silverton clicks with new partner |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=27 September 2010 |date=28 September 2005}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Daily Mirror]]'' quoted another BBC 'insider' as saying that Silverton is \"...pushy beyond belief. Behind her big superficial smile she can be a really aggressive, manipulative monster who always gets what she wants.\"<ref name=\"Webster\" /> Hayton merely cited \"incompatibility\" with Silverton as his reason and when his managers refused to move Silverton to another time slot, he left. Silverton was in the peculiar position of having to go through the morning's paper review live on air the morning the story broke, avoiding any discussion of the story and chiding her new co-anchor when he looked to refer to it.<ref name=\"Telegraph\" /> Hayton said that he left the BBC \"without bitterness or rancour\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\" />\n\nHowever, several figures spoke up for Silverton. [[Jon Sopel (journalist)|Jon Sopel]], a fellow BBC News 24 presenter, who was Silverton's co-anchor at News 24 for several months, commented on the incident saying: \"She's warm and friendly. With Kate, what you see is what you get - she's bright, lively, talented and vivacious. I like and trust her. Yes, she's ambitious... but aren't we all?\"<ref name=\"Webster\" />\n\n[[Rod Liddle]], who was allegedly hit by Silverton in 2003,<ref name=autogenerated1 /> nevertheless defended his former co-presenter. Liddle said: \"Kate is intelligent, attractive and has strong opinions. She was absolutely lovely, good fun, professional, intelligent and devoid of the usual afflictions of TV presenters - [[narcissism]] and greed.\"<ref>Adam Sherwin [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1799324,00.html \"Personality clash drives newsman from BBC\",] ''The Times'', 27 September 2005.</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSilverton married Mike Heron in 2010. On 5 November 2011, Silverton gave birth to a baby girl. Her baby daughter was eventually conceived naturally, after four unsuccessful cycles of IVF. After losing an ovary during an operation to remove a cyst at the age of 29, Silverton had been told that she was unlikely to get pregnant naturally.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news |last=Sawer |first=Patrick |title=Kate Silverton announces second pregnancy with 'thumbs up' scan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/10597035/Kate-Silverton-announces-second-pregnancy-with-thumbs-up-scan.html |accessdate=1 February 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=25 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January 2014, at the age of 43, Silverton announced that she was pregnant with her second child. She used her Twitter account to break the news, stating: \"Mike and I are very happy to share that Clemency is set to become a big sister this summer.\"<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Their second child, a son, was born on 26 June 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Silverton |first=Kate |title=Twitter |url=https://twitter.com/katesilverton1/status/482769351851114496.html |accessdate=3 July 2014 |date=28 June 2014 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nSilverton is 5&nbsp;ft 10in tall. In August 2018, she said the producers of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' had custom-made shoes created for her because none in the ''Strictly'' wardrobe were big enough for her above-average size nine feet.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC's Kate Silverton: 'Strictly had to make special shoes for my big feet' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/08/18/bbcs-kate-silverton-strictly-had-make-special-shoes-big-feet/ |accessdate=1 October 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Cosmetic surgery lawsuit ===\nIn January 2008, Silverton sued a clinic after an allegedly botched cosmetic surgery procedure for treatment of [[acne]] scars. Silverton said that the procedure caused a severe skin reaction and she had to take two weeks off work after the treatment. The lawsuit filed for unspecified monetary damages.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mark |last=Raby |url=http://www.tgdaily.com/content/view/35809/118 |title=BBC anchor sues over facial surgery for HDTV makeover |publisher=Tgdaily.com |date=28 January 2008 |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321050154/http://www.tgdaily.com/content/view/35809/118 |archivedate=21 March 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=1176615|name=Kate Silverton}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.katesilverton.com}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/breakfast/presenters/4599291.stm BBC profile]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7133119.stm Report to announce new 2000 bulletin]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Natasha Kaplinsky]]\n{{s-ttl|title=Main Presenter of ''[[BBC News Summary|BBC News 8pm summary]]''| years=2007 \u2013 2008}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Ellie Crisell]]}}\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Ben Brown (journalist)|Ben Brown]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Main Saturday Presenter of ''[[BBC Weekend News]]''\n| years = 2009 - present\n}}\n{{s-inc\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Louise Minchin]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Deputy Presenter of ''[[BBC News at One]]''\n| years = 2009 \u2013 2012\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Sian Williams]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = Sian Williams\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Deputy Presenter of ''[[BBC News at One]]''\n| years = 2013 - present\n}}\n{{s-inc\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = New Post\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Main Relief Presenter of ''[[BBC News at One]]''\n| years = 2012 \u2013 2013\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Simon McCoy]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Silverton, Kate}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:ITV regional newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:British television presenters]]\n[[Category:English television journalists]]\n[[Category:English women journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Waltham Abbey, Essex]]\n[[Category:British women television journalists]]\n[[Category:Women radio presenters]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Cuthbert's Society, Durham]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kate Silverton\n| image              = Geneva International Motor Show 2018, Le Grand-Saconnex (1X7A0488).jpg\n| caption            = \n| birthname          = Kate Silverton\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = [[Waltham Abbey (town)|Waltham Abbey]], [[Essex]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = [[University of Durham]]\n| occupation         = [[Journalist]], [[broadcaster]], [[newsreader]]\n| years_active       = 1992\u2013present\n| alias              = \n| title              = \n| family             = \n| spouse             = {{marriage| Mike Heron|18 December 2010}}\n| domesticpartner    = \n| children           = 2\n| relatives          = \n| nationality        = [[British people|British]]\n| religion           = \n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| credits            = ''[[BBC Breakfast]]''<br>''[[BBC News at Six]]''<br>''[[BBC News at Ten]]''<br>''[[BBC News Summary]]''<br>''[[BBC Weekend News]]''<br>''[[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC News Channel]]''<br>''[[BBC World News]]''<br>''[[GMT (TV series)|GMT]]''\n| agent              = \n| URL                = \n}}\n'''Kate Silverton''' is an English journalist and broadcaster working for the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Newsroom spat forces BBC anchor to quit |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1499234/Newsroom-spat-forces-BBC-anchor-to-quit.html |accessdate=1 February 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=26 September 2005}}</ref> Generally a main and relief presenter for the BBC, Silverton can be seen regularly presenting the ''[[BBC News at One]]'', ''[[BBC News at Six]]'', ''[[BBC News at Ten]]'', and ''[[BBC Weekend News]]'', and is the current Deputy Presenter of the ''[[BBC News at One]]'' as well as making occasional appearances on the [[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC News Channel]] and [[BBC World News]]. In 2018 she participated in the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 16)|sixteenth series]] of BBC's ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'', paired with professional dancer [[Aljaz Skorjanec]] finishing in 8th place. \n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nSilverton was born in [[Waltham Abbey (town)|Waltham Abbey]] in [[Essex]], England, the daughter of Terry Silverton, a [[Hackney carriage|black-cab driver]]-turned-registered [[hypnotherapy|hypnotherapist]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/5292044/Kate-Silverton-now-its-her-turn-to-make-the-news.html |title=Kate Silverton: now it's her turn to make the news |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=8 May 2009 |accessdate=27 September 2010 |location=London |first=Celia |last=Walden}}</ref> and Patricia Silverton. Silverton has two sisters, Claire and Amy. Silverton attended [[West Hatch High School]] in [[Chigwell]], Essex, where she was a junior swimming champion. She also competed in the [[triathlon]].<ref name=\"Webster\">{{cite news |last=Webster |first=Nick |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/tm_objectid=16202006&method=full&siteid=94762&headline=attractive--ambitious-and-very-scary--tv-newsreader-kate-silverton-is-the---kaplinsky-klone--name_page.html |title=Attractive, ambitious and very scary |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=3 October 2005 |accessdate=27 September 2010}}</ref> She was a [[Girl Guide]] and gained the [[Queen's Guide (Girlguiding UK)|Queen's Guide Award]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Centenary of Guiding |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/womanshour/01/2009_35_mon.shtml |work=Woman's Hour |publisher=BBC Radio 4 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nSilverton graduated from [[St. Cuthbert's Society]], a college at [[Durham University]] with a Bachelor of Science degree in [[Psychology]], having previously studied Arabic and Middle Eastern history for a year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bigcat/presenters/katesilverton/ |title=Kate Silverton joins the Big Cat team |work=BBC |accessdate=27 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Early career ===\nSilverton worked for a London-based bank before becoming a journalist. She trained with the [[BBC]], working on ''[[BBC Look North (North East and Cumbria)|Look North]]'' news before becoming a reporter and presenter at [[ITV Tyne Tees|Tyne Tees Television]].\n\nShe was a panellist on [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]'s ''[[The Wright Stuff]]''. She also featured on ''[[The Heaven and Earth Show]]'', ''Big Strong Boys'',<ref>{{cite news |last=Jury |first=Louise |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/viewers-put-off-their-breakfast-by-bbc-presenters-psychedelic-blouse-480769.html |title=Viewers put off their breakfast by BBC presenter's psychedelic blouse |newspaper=The Independent |date=2 June 2006 |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> and ''Weekend Breakfast'' on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], before joining [[BBC News]].\n\nIn 2003, Silverton allegedly hit [[Rod Liddle]], the former editor of [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme, during a pilot for a new political show. Liddle said: \"I made a stupid comment about the disabled which Kate rightly took exception to.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news |last=Macgregor |first=Fiona |url=http://news.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=474&id=1999392005 |date=27 September 2005|title=Here is the news ... I cannot work with that woman, so I quit |newspaper=Scotland on Sunday |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===BBC News===\n{{main|BBC News}}\nFrom 2005 until December 2007, Silverton was a presenter on [[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC News 24]] and also a regular relief presenter for ''[[BBC Breakfast]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}}\n\nIn December 2007, she was named as the presenter of the ''BBC News 8 p.m. summary'', a 90-second round-up of the news shown on [[BBC One]], which she presented for two months. She presented the ''[[BBC News at One]]'' from February to August 2008, whilst main presenter [[Sophie Raworth]] was on maternity leave.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.katesilverton.com |title=Kate Silverton to present news bulletin - Silverton's official website |publisher=Katesilverton.com |accessdate=27 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, Silverton revealed in an interview in ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper that she had been offered a main presenter role for the relaunch of [[5 News]] in 2007 which she declined.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n[[BBC Scotland]] apologised to viewers in August 2010, after Silverton swore at the end of a news bulletin on live television. Viewers in Scotland were the only ones who heard the words. A spokesman for BBC Scotland said: \"Kate thought she was off-air at the time. The microphones hadn't been faded down and the mistake only went out in Scotland.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Stephen |title=BBC presenter Kate Silverton's 'bloody' big gaffe - heard only in Scotland |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/bbc-presenter-kate-silvertons-bloody-1067200 |accessdate=19 November 2013 |date=15 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nSilverton took maternity leave in October 2011, and returned to the ''News at One'' in April 2012. Until May 2012, she was the deputy presenter of the BBC ''News at One'',<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/biographies/biogs/news/katesilverton.shtml Kate Silverton] - BBC Press Office profile</ref> presenting on Mondays and when main presenter Sophie Raworth was unavailable. [[Sian Williams]] later took over this role. Silverton returned to the deputy role in October 2013 to cover for Williams' leave. However, Williams later left the BBC so Silverton regained her role.\n\nSilverton returned to the BBC News in July 2015 after maternity leave, and was seconded to BBC Radio 4. She returned from her secondment in April 2016.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\n=== Other BBC projects ===\nOn 1 April 2008, alongside the [[historian]] [[Dan Snow]], she presented live coverage of the celebrations held at [[RAF Fairford]] for the 90th Birthday of the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref>{{cite news |title=DOCUMENTARY: Royal Air Force: Celebrating 90 Years |url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/52048/DOCUMENTARY-Royal-Air-Force-Celebrating-90-Years-2-15pm-BBC1 |accessdate=28 October 2013 |newspaper=Daily Express |date=11 July 2008}}</ref> In 2008, Silverton joined the presenting team for ''[[Big Cat Diary]]'' on [[BBC One]].<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC: Big Cat Live 2008 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bigcat/about/|work=BBC|accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> She co-presented coverage of ''[[New Year Live]]'' aboard {{HMS|Belfast|C35|6}} in London on 31 December 2008 on BBC One with [[Nick Knowles]].<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC One: New Year Live |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00gd5cn |work=BBC |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, she appeared as a mentor in the [[BBC Two]] series ''[[The Speaker]]'', offering her advice on good storytelling and public speaking.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC: The Speaker |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/speaker/improve/storytelling/ |work=BBC |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, she presented a documentary called ''10 Things You Need to Know About Sleep'', which looked at different ways to deal with [[insomnia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=BBC One - 10 Things You Need to Know About Sleep |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00j08h7 |work=BBC |accessdate=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010, she presented the Sunday morning show on BBC Radio 5 Live, running from 09:30 to 11:00.<ref>{{cite web |title=Radio 5 Live's new-look weekend line-up revealed |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/09_september/03/5live.shtml |work=BBC Press Office |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Silverton interviewed [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]], who called for a halt to the killing of rhinos for their horns in Africa.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince William hits out at rhino poachers |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18489579 |work=BBC News |date=19 June 2012 |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> Silverton has also acted as a stand-in presenter for the [[Radio Four]] series ''[[Last Word]]''.\n\n===''Strictly Come Dancing'' ===\nBetween 8 September and 18 November 2018, Silverton participated in the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 16)|sixteenth series]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0bk1pbm |title=BBC One - Strictly Come Dancing, Series 16, Launch |publisher=BBC One |date=September 8, 2018 |accessdate=September 8, 2018}}</ref> with professional dance partner [[Alja\u017e Skorjanec]]. The couple were eliminated in Week 9 (Blackpool), losing a dance-off against [[Graeme Swann]] and his partner [[Oti Mabuse]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n|- style=\"text-align:Center; background:#ccc;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Week # \n! rowspan=\"2\" | Dance / Song \n! colspan=\"5\" | Judges' score \n! rowspan=\"2\" | Result \n|- style=\"text-align:center; background:#ccc;\"\n| style=\"width:10%; \" |Revel Horwood\n| style=\"width:10%; \" |Bussell\n| style=\"width:10%; \" |Ballas\n| style=\"width:10%; \" |Tonioli\n| style=\"width:10%; \" |'''Total'''\n|- style=\"text-align: center; background:#faf6f6;\"\n|1\n|[[Cha-cha-cha (dance)|Cha-cha-cha]] / \"[[Kiss (Prince song)|Kiss]]\"\n|4\n|6\n|4\n|6\n|20\n|No Elimination\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|2\n|[[Tango]] / \"[[No Roots (song)|No Roots]]\" \n|6\n|7\n|7\n|7\n|27\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|3\n|[[Foxtrot]] / \"[[Why Don't You Do Right?]]\"\n|6\n|7\n|8\n|8\n|29\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|4\n|[[Samba]] / \"[[Africa (Toto song)|Africa]]\"\n|4\n|5\n|5\n|6\n|20\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\n|5\n|[[Viennese waltz]] / \"Finally Mine\"\n|6\n|6\n|6\n|8{{ref|A|A}}\n|26\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|6\n|[[Rhumba]] / \"[[Skin (Rag'n'Bone Man song)|Skin]]\"\n|4\n|6\n|5\n|5\n|<span style=\"color:red\">''20''</span>\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|7\n|[[Argentine tango]] / \"Assassin's Tango\"\n|4\n|6\n|6\n|7\n|23\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|8\n|[[Quickstep]] / \"[[I Want You to Want Me]]\"\n|7\n|7\n|8\n|8\n|30\n|Safe\n|- style=\"text-align:center; \n|9\n|[[American Smooth]] / \"[[Everlasting Love]]\"\n|7\n|7\n|8\n|8\n|30\n|Eliminated\n|}\n;Notes\n;*<small><span style=\"color:red\">'''Red'''</span> number indicates Kate & Alja\u017e were at the bottom of the leaderboard</small>\n:{{note|A|A}} [[Alfonso Ribeiro]] filled in for Tonioli\n\n== Philip Hayton incident ==\nIn September 2005, Silverton drew media attention when her BBC News 24 co-newsreader [[Philip Hayton]], who had worked for the BBC for 37 years, resigned his position six months into a year's contract, citing issues of \"incompatibility\" with Silverton.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC newsreader quits over 'clash' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4283824.stm |accessdate=29 October 2013 |work=BBC News |date=26 September 2005}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', without substantiation and quoting an unnamed 'insider', reported that Hayton turned to Silverton during a break and said \"I don't like you\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news |last=Alleyne |first=Richard |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1499354/Chemistry-as-Silverton-clicks-with-new-partner.html |title=Chemistry as Silverton clicks with new partner |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=27 September 2010 |date=28 September 2005}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Daily Mirror]]'' quoted another BBC 'insider' as saying that Silverton is \"...pushy beyond belief. Behind her big superficial smile she can be a really aggressive, manipulative monster who always gets what she wants.\"<ref name=\"Webster\" /> Hayton merely cited \"incompatibility\" with Silverton as his reason and when his managers refused to move Silverton to another time slot, he left. Silverton was in the peculiar position of having to go through the morning's paper review live on air the morning the story broke, avoiding any discussion of the story and chiding her new co-anchor when he looked to refer to it.<ref name=\"Telegraph\" /> Hayton said that he left the BBC \"without bitterness or rancour\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\" />\n\nHowever, several figures spoke up for Silverton. [[Jon Sopel (journalist)|Jon Sopel]], a fellow BBC News 24 presenter, who was Silverton's co-anchor at News 24 for several months, commented on the incident saying: \"She's warm and friendly. With Kate, what you see is what you get - she's bright, lively, talented and vivacious. I like and trust her. Yes, she's ambitious... but aren't we all?\"<ref name=\"Webster\" />\n\n[[Rod Liddle]], who was allegedly hit by Silverton in 2003,<ref name=autogenerated1 /> nevertheless defended his former co-presenter. Liddle said: \"Kate is intelligent, attractive and has strong opinions. She was absolutely lovely, good fun, professional, intelligent and devoid of the usual afflictions of TV presenters - [[narcissism]] and greed.\"<ref>Adam Sherwin [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1799324,00.html \"Personality clash drives newsman from BBC\",] ''The Times'', 27 September 2005.</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSilverton married Mike Heron in 2010. On 5 November 2011, Silverton gave birth to a baby girl. Her baby daughter was eventually conceived naturally, after four unsuccessful cycles of IVF. After losing an ovary during an operation to remove a cyst at the age of 29, Silverton had been told that she was unlikely to get pregnant naturally.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news |last=Sawer |first=Patrick |title=Kate Silverton announces second pregnancy with 'thumbs up' scan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/10597035/Kate-Silverton-announces-second-pregnancy-with-thumbs-up-scan.html |accessdate=1 February 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=25 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January 2014, at the age of 43, Silverton announced that she was pregnant with her second child. She used her Twitter account to break the news, stating: \"Mike and I are very happy to share that Clemency is set to become a big sister this summer.\"<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Their second child, a son, was born on 26 June 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Silverton |first=Kate |title=Twitter |url=https://twitter.com/katesilverton1/status/482769351851114496.html |accessdate=3 July 2014 |date=28 June 2014 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nSilverton is 5&nbsp;ft 10in tall. In August 2018, she said the producers of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' had custom-made shoes created for her because none in the ''Strictly'' wardrobe were big enough for her above-average size nine feet.<ref>{{cite news |title=BBC's Kate Silverton: 'Strictly had to make special shoes for my big feet' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/08/18/bbcs-kate-silverton-strictly-had-make-special-shoes-big-feet/ |accessdate=1 October 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Cosmetic surgery lawsuit ===\nIn January 2008, Silverton sued a clinic after an allegedly botched cosmetic surgery procedure for treatment of [[acne]] scars. Silverton said that the procedure caused a severe skin reaction and she had to take two weeks off work after the treatment. The lawsuit filed for unspecified monetary damages.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mark |last=Raby |url=http://www.tgdaily.com/content/view/35809/118 |title=BBC anchor sues over facial surgery for HDTV makeover |publisher=Tgdaily.com |date=28 January 2008 |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321050154/http://www.tgdaily.com/content/view/35809/118 |archivedate=21 March 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=1176615|name=Kate Silverton}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.katesilverton.com}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/breakfast/presenters/4599291.stm BBC profile]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7133119.stm Report to announce new 2000 bulletin]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Natasha Kaplinsky]]\n{{s-ttl|title=Main Presenter of ''[[BBC News Summary|BBC News 8pm summary]]''| years=2007 \u2013 2008}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Ellie Crisell]]}}\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Ben Brown (journalist)|Ben Brown]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Main Saturday Presenter of ''[[BBC Weekend News]]''\n| years = 2009 - present\n}}\n{{s-inc\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Louise Minchin]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Deputy Presenter of ''[[BBC News at One]]''\n| years = 2009 \u2013 2012\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Sian Williams]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = Sian Williams\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Deputy Presenter of ''[[BBC News at One]]''\n| years = 2013 - present\n}}\n{{s-inc\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = New Post\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Main Relief Presenter of ''[[BBC News at One]]''\n| years = 2012 \u2013 2013\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Simon McCoy]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Silverton, Kate}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:ITV regional newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:British television presenters]]\n[[Category:English television journalists]]\n[[Category:English women journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Waltham Abbey, Essex]]\n[[Category:British women television journalists]]\n[[Category:Women radio presenters]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Cuthbert's Society, Durham]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:broadcaster\u2192News presenter,newsreader\u2192news presenter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kate_Silverton"}
{"title_page": "Moturoa AFC", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Moturoa AFC\n| image = \n| fullname = Moturoa Association Football and Sports Club\n| nickname = \"the Reds\" - \"Roa\"\n| founded = 1928\n| ground = Onuku Taipari Domain, [[Moturoa]], [[New Plymouth]]\n| capacity = \n| chairman = Scott Manson\n| coach = \n| league = Taranaki Premier League\n| season = 2019\n| position = 1st\n| kit_alt1 = Red shirt with white collar, shorts and socks\n| pattern_b1 = _collarwhite\n| pattern_la1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_ra1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_sh1 = _whitesides\n| pattern_so1 = _whitesides\n| leftarm1 = DD0022\n| body1 = DD0022\n| rightarm1 = DD0022\n| shorts1 = DD0022\n| socks1 = DD0022\n| kit_alt2 = Blue and white shirt, blue shorts and socks.\n| pattern_b2 = _blueshouldersandchest\n| pattern_la2 = _whitelower\n| pattern_ra2 = _whitelower\n| pattern_sh2 = _whitesides\n| pattern_so2 = _whitesides\n| leftarm2 = 0000BB\n| body2 = 0000BB\n| rightarm2 = 0000BB\n| shorts2 = 0000BB\n| socks2 = 0000BB\n| website = https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/\n}}\n'''Moturoa AFC''' is one of [[New Zealand]]'s oldest [[association football]] clubs. Based in [[New Plymouth]], the club traces its development back to the New Plymouth Watersiders team<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/70915|title=Watersides Soccer Team, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref> from the early years of the 20th century, and has historic  links to each of the many schools from the area and greater New Plymouth.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/80812|title=Motoroa Football Team|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nThe club refers to itself as the \"Traditional home of [[Taranaki Region|Taranaki]] football\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Moturoa AFC |url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/ |website=Moturoa AFC}}</ref> Its clubrooms and home ground are at the Onuku Taipari Domain, Ngamotu Road, New Plymouth.\n\nMoturoa AFC is home to many junior sides in the Taranaki age-group grades, providing a footballing base for players from the many surrounding schools.\n\nThe club also has three men's sides and two women's sides.\n\nThough not currently playing in the upper echelons of New Zealand football, Moturoa AFC has a rich history with the club having success in many regional and national competitions.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103150|title=Moturoa Association Football Club, 1960|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\n==2019 Season==\n\nThe Taranaki Premier League team are defending Taranaki Champions and have won three successive premierships in a row, completing the 2019 season unbeaten in the league and retaining the league challenge trophy.<ref name=\"website\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/|title=New Plymouth Moturoa AFC Football|website=moturoaafcnz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nThe team also hold the Sheffield United Plate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/|title=New Plymouth {{!}} Moturoa AFC {{!}} Football|website=moturoaafcnz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> won in the pre-season by defeating the 2018 Central Federation Cup winners Eltham AFC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.centralfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/67908|title=A Men's Federation Cup final for the ages!|website=www.centralfootball.co.nz|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Moturoa Womens Premiership team are also defending Taranaki Champions, winning the league challenge trophy along with the Central Federation Cup and Duchess Cup titles.<ref name=\"website\" />\n\n==Early History==\n\nThe Moturoa School opened in 1923 after years of deliberation.\n\nThe Watersiders won the Duff Rose Bowl in 1927 defeating Rangers (Fitzroy) in the final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19270815.2.33|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Both the Watersiders and related Wanderers team dissolved after this year. \n\nSince the games inception in New Plymouth in 1904 there had been a steady turn over of clubs. Omata, Mangorei Swifts, Carrington, New Plymouth, Star and Tukapa were among the originals from Taranaki's largest town. Due to the first world war most of these clubs were never brought out of recess. New Plymouth AFC was the first club to re-emerge in 1922 playing a well drilled Hawera who had played matches with teams from Wanganui along with the South Taranaki clubs. The New Plymouth teams relied mainly on the port and it's visiting ships for competition during the post war years.\n\nAfter 1923 in New Plymouth there were four teams. The Wanderers, The Watersiders, Albion FC and Caledonian. These teams were later joined by Rangers and Pirates from eastern New Plymouth in 1927, both often played at the Bellringer Estate home of today's Peringa United.\n\nThe name Moturoa was first used with the Taranaki Football Association (TFA) for the 1928 season.<ref name=\"paperspast.natlib.govt.nz\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280611.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> \n\nOriginally Moturoa FC was a shortlived rugby club, started by the Breakwater Sports Committee at the kiosk at Ngamotu Beach in early 1914 before amalgamating with the Star club. The club retained one junior team that played in the club's colour, white, with a star emblem.\n\nOne of the first TFA delegates representing Moturoa was Mr. J. McKay in 1928.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19290416.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> He had moved onto Caledonian by 1933 and in 1935 to New Plymouth Thistle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330426.2.69|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1928 - In early June in the Julian Cup, Caledonian inflict a heavy 4 - 0 defeat to Moturoa.<ref name=\"paperspast.natlib.govt.nz\"/> In late August Caledonian beat Moturoa again, this time in the Duff Cup, a huge score-line of 10 -0 recorded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280827.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> By early September results improved, still playing in the Duff Cup, Moturoa beat Rangers 3 - 0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280910.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1929 - Moturoa's intermediate team, competing for the Plunket Cup, lost the final to Caledonian.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> The junior championship competition was keenly contested this year with many very promising players being found in the junior ranks, the game was said to have a very bright future in Taranaki. Moturoa made up for the Plunket Cup loss by winning the Plum Cup, the Chinese Cup and the Taranaki junior championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300408.2.51|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1930 - The TFA had a special meeting after receiving a letter from the New Plymouth clubs in the Northern Sub-Committee, with the Julian Cup lacking in entries. Only Stratford, Celtic (Hawera) and Albion had entered clubs. Moturoa, Caledonian, Rangers (Fitzroy) along with the club Pirates (New Plymouth) citing travel around Taranaki as detrimental to the progress of their junior competitions. A resolution was made by Mr. G.Littlejohn, that was met with approval by all the club representatives, except Rangers who had to consult their players. Moturoa's first game was scheduled for the 10th of May against Pirates,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300501.2.40|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> the result being a 5 - 1 win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300512.2.14|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> By the 19th of May, Rangers had dropped out for the season. Moturoa played Hawera team Celtic, losing 3 - 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300519.2.9|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>  Early June, Moturoa defaulted to Albion. Celtic, Pirates, Caledonian and Stratford managing to field teams.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300609.2.20|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> In early July Moturoa was drawn to play Stratford away in the first round of the Chinese Cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300703.2.8|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> A match day later, Stratford became the winners of the Chinese Cup for the season beating Hawera, with Moturoa facing Caledonian in a 4 - 4 draw for the Duff Cup (Duff Rose Bowl) the same weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300714.2.21|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> The attempt to win the years Priest Shield tournament was not successful. With two teams entered (A and B), Moturoa were losing semi-finalists to Caledonian after the match ended drawn and was decided by a corner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300811.2.52|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1931 - In attendance at the TFA AGM were Moturoa club delegates, F. Roper and G. Rendell. The draw was made for the Julian Cup with Moturoa playing Albion in the first round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19310415.2.52|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Later in the year, Moturoa's senior team won the annual six-a-side competition for the Priest Shield at New Plymouth. There were six teams in the competition, which was conducted at Western Park. The players in the final for Moturoa were: R. Johns, R. and F. Roper, Anderson, White, Smith. And for Stratford: Grierson, Thomson, Henderson, O\u2019Shannessey, McGrory, Elgar. The final score was Moturoa 3  Stratford 1. White getting a hat-trick for Moturoa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19310914.2.68|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1932 - The season concluded with the annual Priest Shield contest at Western Park. Moturoa again exiting in the semi-finals, this year to Albion 2 - 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19320905.2.6|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1933 - At the TFA's annual meeting in late April, held at Smith's Tea Rooms in Stratford, Waitara were accepted as an affiliated member of the association, giving further competition for Moturoa and the teams in the northern sub-committee. Albion were congratulated for winning all of the trophies in the prior season. A loan was made of \u00a35 to the northern sub-committee. Moturoa's delegates at the meeting were G.E. Roper and R.J. Page. Times had changed in South Taranaki, with the Stratford and two Hawera clubs listed as inactive. The season start date was set for May the 6th.<ref name=\":5\" /> Stratford turned this around and managed to field a team by May.<ref name=\":5\"/> The Julian Cup became a one-round competition. In all competitions except the Duff Cup, it was decided that the home team retained all the collections taken up at the match. A life sentence handed down to a player from an undisclosed club by the executive for the \"unfortunate breach of the rules of good conduct\", was reduced by the New Zealand Football Association (NZFA) to a five year suspension.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330426.2.69|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Moturoa played the newly affiliated Waitara for the first time in the middle of May. The match result being a draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330515.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The week after this significant fixture the club faced Caledonian losing 2 - 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330522.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Following that match another loss, this time to Albion 6 - 0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330529.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Moturoa played Stratford, at Stratford, in June in their final Julian Cup game for the season. The game ended in a one all draw, both goals from the first half. The Moturoa team list read as follows; Thompson, Roper, Simpson, Anderson, Bensley, Johns, White, Kenny, Christensen, a second Thompson and Grey. The Julian Cup was won again by Albion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330612.2.6|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The first round of the Duff Rose Bowl saw Moturoa defeat the recent Julian Cup winners Albion, 2 - 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330626.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the second week of July the TFA suspended club football as the Taranaki representative team were travelling to Manawatu. An exhibition game of Probables v Possibles at Victoria Park used the remaining local players, with the hope of stimulating interest in the code again in South Taranaki. Moturoa's representatives scheduled to play in the fixture were, R. Kenny, R and F Roper, J. Thompson and A. Smith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330707.2.27|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nThe executive of the TFA met on the 11th of July at New Plymouth, Mr. G. E Roper from Moturoa agreed to broadcast talks on the game from local radio station 2XP. His first subject said to be \"The Organisation of Association Football in Schools\". At this time there was a considerable effort to establish the game in the schools. Stratford reporting that Tokaora and Waingongoro schools had requested balls. The executive considered the report of the referee, Mr. R. Swan, in regards to J. Thompson from Moturoa, and his sending from the field in the match against Waitara at [[Fitzroy, Taranaki|Fitzroy]] on July 1. Moturoa submitted a resolution and made representations in support, Thomson explained his view of the matter. It was decided to censure Thomson, but to take no further action as it was considered he had been sufficiently punished in being stood down from the Taranaki team that travelled to [[Manawatu District|Manawatu]] the match day prior. It was also noted in the minutes that Moturoa was to be asked to explain in \u201ccounting out\u201d the referee after a recent match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330712.2.61|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn bad weather in late July, Moturoa played Pirates in the Duff Rose Bowl. The score, unconfirmed, a possible 0 - 0 draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330724.2.4|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n1934 - Moturoa defeated Stratford away. Mr. Johns, a Moturoa supporter, stepping in for the referee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330828.2.7|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Moturoa were runners up this year in the Julian Cup to winners Stratford AFC.\n\n1935 - Mr. Peter Gardner, who resided at Harbour Street, Moturoa, and Mr. E. Kenny were Moturoa's TFA delegates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19350417.2.45|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Gardner would later join New Plymouth Old Boys after WW2.\n\nMoturoa were one of the three New Plymouth sides in the Taranaki League for the Julian Cup in 1935, the other two being New Plymouth Albion and New Plymouth Thistle.\n\nIn 1938 the constitution of the club was first written.\n\n==Moturoa's Magyars==\n\nAttila Varga,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/obituaries/674894/Attila-Varga|title=Attila Varga|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> Lotsy Varga and Lotsy Polyanszky were prominent players for the club in the late 50s and 60s.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103151|title=Moturoa Soccer, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> All three players ended up being headhunted by Wellington-based [[Wellington United|Hungaria]]. Still considered by many to have been one of this country's best sides.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/obituaries/674894/Attila-Varga|title=Attila Varga|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/sport/105996458/hungarian-influence-remembered-as-wellington-united-marks-125th-anniversary|title=Hungarian influence remembered as Wellington United marks 125th anniversary|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nPolyanszky left Moturoa at the end of the successful 1960 season after being spotted playing for Moturoa against North Shore United in the Chatham Cup semi final at Blandford Park. In the 1961 season Polyanszky played in the Chatham Cup final for North Shore United. And eventually became player/coach of Hungaria by 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Small Price to Pay: Refugees from Hitler in New Zealand 1986\u201346|last=Beaglehole|first=Ann|date=1988|publisher=Bridget Williams Books|isbn=9780868616353|doi = 10.7810/9780868616353}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/photograph/3897/hungaria-association-football-club-1969|title=Hungaria Association Football Club, 1969|last=Taonga|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|website=teara.govt.nz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> It has been said he was the most skillful footballer ever to grace a football field in New Zealand by many varied commentators of the game.\n\nHungaria played in the Central Region League before being invited to join the first [[New Zealand National Soccer League]] in 1970. It was the club's only season in the National League forming a composite team with Miramar Rangers as Wellington City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1524.htm|title=Wellington United|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973 Hungaria went solo again, this time in Division Two of the Central League, finishing second, to Moturoa United. Moturoa's hometown rivals Old Boys were also in Division Two in 1973.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZClubSoccer/id396.htm|title=1973|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Moturoa drew with Hungaria at home 1 - 1, and lost away in Wellington 2 - 1, the close competition between the two teams shown in the almost equal statistics.<ref name=\":4\" /> Moturoa were promoted for the 1974 season as champions. Hungaria, as runners up had to wait another year in Division Two. The two clubs crossed over in 1974 with Moturoa being relegated back to Division Two and Hungaria taking their place in Division One.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZClubSoccer/id397.htm|title=1974|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==Chatham Cup==\n\nMoturoa has competed for the [[Chatham Cup]] since [[1949 Chatham Cup|1949]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/55223|title=Motorua [Moturoa], Soccer Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\n1949 - MAFC were beaten 6-1 at Western Park by [[Ohakea]].\n\n1950 - The club was drawn against the multi-national [[RNZAF]] team again suffering the same fate, though this time with the more respectable result of 5-4 at Ohakea. \n\nThe club shirt colour from this time was blue and white quarters with white shorts and black socks. \n\n1951 - The club goes into recess. Partially triggered from the effects of the [[1951 New Zealand waterfront dispute|waterfront dispute]] of this year on the wider [[Moturoa]] community.\n\n1953 - Life member, Hans Halder begins first of 25 years as MAFC President. Herb Hutton, life-member and first team player from 1945 to 1965, would resume the role of MAFC Secretary continuing until stepping down in 1972. \n\nThe club comes out of recess with a new shirt colour of red, with white shorts, and red and black hooped socks.\n\n1954 - Moturoa defeat [[Wanganui]] New Settlers 1-0  followed by a 4-2 win versus Palmerston North End, drawing a home game for the North Island quarter final and being soundly defeated 3-0 by Wellington's [[Stop Out]] at Western Park.\n\n1955 - [[Kiwi United]] knock Taranaki qualifiers New Plymouth Old Boys out in early August 5-2.\n\n1956 - Moturoa win the Taranaki Championship for the first time.\n\n[[Ted Meuli]] capped NZ test cricketer and NZ Universities football representative,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Salient12061949-t1-body-d28-d9.html|title=Soccer {{!}} NZETC|website=nzetc.victoria.ac.nz|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> begins to play for the club throughout this time<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103150|title=Moturoa Association Football Club, 1960|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> after spending his prior years with New Plymouth rivals, Old Boys.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/60097|title=Old Boys Soccer, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n1957 - An away game for Moturoa at the Sportsground against the Wanganui Settlers was lost 4-2. \n\n1958 - Stratford AFC qualify as Taranaki preliminary winners, knocked out by Kiwi United 3-2 at Western Park, New Plymouth.\n\n[[1959 Chatham Cup|1959]] - Moturoa beat Stratford at Western Park 4-1, starting one of the best cup runs in the clubs history. In the next round [[Wanganui Athletic]] were beaten 3-1 at [[Cooks Gardens]]. In the next round Napier Athletic travelled across to New Plymouth and were beaten 6-0 at Western Park. In the quarter final at the [[Basin Reserve]] in Wellington, Moturoa were beaten by [[Miramar Rangers]] 3-2.\n\n1960 - Moturoa win the first round 6-0 against Wanganui Settlers. In the next round Kiwi United were beaten 4-3. In the quarter final [[Brooklyn Northern United AFC|Northern]] were beaten 3-1 at Western Park.    \n\nIn the Chatham Cup semi final Moturoa travelled to Auckland to play [[North Shore United]] at [[Blandford Park]]. The match was lost 10-2, one of the heaviest losses in the clubs history.    \n\nThe 1960 season is one of most successful in the clubs history. Starting with the [[Kawerau|Kawerau Town]] pre-season tournament and ending with the club representing Taranaki and bringing home the Brown Shield for the first and only time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZRepSoccer/id1653.htm|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> by defeating Poverty Bay in the final of the tournament.     \n\nThe Brown Shield results from 1960 were, round one v Wanganui 6-1, round two v [[Manawatu]] 4-3, semi final v [[Bay of Plenty]] 3-1 and the final v Poverty Bay 2-1.    \n\nThe Brown Shield winning team of 1960 consisted of the players, G. Collett, A. Varga, G. Gregory (GK), H. Hutton, M. Fugett, T. Hawley, J. Marshall (captain), L. Varga, A. Evans, L. Polyanszky, T. Verbeet and coached by C. Wells.\u00a0 \u00a0\nThe Brown Shield originated in 1892. Taranaki first challenged for the shield in 1905, playing out a 1-1 draw against holders Wellington at New Plymouth on a Thursday in late September. C. Wilson scoring for Taranaki. The team made up with players from the Omata, New Plymouth and Waitara teams. In 1906 the next challenge was also without success, losing 4-0 to Wellington in a match played at [[Eltham]] in early September. The team made up with players from South Taranaki settlements [[Auroa]], [[Kaponga]], [[Hawera]] and Eltham.     \n\n1961 - Moturoa play New Plymouth City winning 4-0 at Western Park. In June, Wanganui Settlers were defeated 3-2 at the Oval in Wanganui. In July, Moturoa travelled to Napier, the match went to [[Napier Rovers]], the score unrecorded. \n\nOne of MAFC's best cup performances came in [[1962 Chatham Cup|1962]], with four home games at Western Park. In the Taranaki final Moturoa beat NP Old Boys 1-0. In the first round Wanganui Athletic were defeated 1-0. In the second round [[Red Sox Manawatu|St. Andrews]] were beaten 6-1. A quarter final with [[Seatoun AFC]] was won 3-1, leading to a semi-final against [[Hamilton Technical Old Boys]]. \n\nTechnical Old Boys won 4-0 in a match played before about 2000 people at [[Seddon Park]], Hamilton becoming the first North Island club outside of Auckland or Wellington to qualify for the final. Which spoke volumes for Moturoa, not only because they faced a Hamilton team with three [[List of New Zealand international footballers|New Zealand internationals]], but Technical proceeded to beat [[Otago]]\u2019s [[Northern AFC|Northern]] \u2013 who had won the [[1961 Chatham Cup|1961]] cup, 4-1 in the final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.melvilleunited.co.nz/semifinals-celebration/|title=Semifinals celebration|website=Melville United AFC|language=en-NZ|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n\n1963 - St. Andrews were beaten 5-2 at Western Park. At Wembley Park in the next match Wanganui United beat Moturoa 6-4.\n\nIn 1964 the club changes the playing kit colour to white shirts, red shorts and white socks. \n\nWanganui United were the opponent in round one, again at Wembley Park, a 6-2 defeat ended the cup for Moturoa.\n\nIn the [[1965 Chatham Cup|1965]] Chatham Cup, Moturoa were beaten in the 3rd round, 3-2 at [[Waitara, New Zealand|Waitara]]. \n\nWaitara had beaten [[Spotswood College|Spotswood]] 7-5 aet while Moturoa had beaten Old Boys 3-1 in the second round. Waitara would beat Wanganui United 3-1 in round four, and depart the competition in round five with a 2-0 loss to Napier Rovers. \n\nIn [[1966 Chatham Cup|1966]] MAFC begin wearing a full red playing kit for the first time.  \n\nIn round two of the Chatham Cup, Waitara were beaten 6-3. In round three, New Plymouth United were beaten 6-0. The next match saw the first fixture between Moturoa and [[Wairarapa United|Masterton Athletic]], a 5-2 victory. In round five Napier Rovers were beaten 4-2. In a replay of the 1959 quarter final Moturoa go out again at the hands of eventual winners of the 1966 cup. [[Miramar Rangers]] this time travelled to New Plymouth winning the tie 3-0 at Western Park. Its side featuring the country\u2019s leading goalkeeper at the time [[Peter Whiting (footballer)|Peter Whiting]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miramarrangers.co.nz/club-history|title=CLUB HISTORY|website=MIRAMAR RANGERS AFC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> \n\n1967 - Old Boys were beaten 3-0 in round one, New Plymouth United 6-3 in round two, in round three Napier Rovers defeat Moturoa 6-2 in Napier. \n\n1968 - In round three Moturoa beat Old Boys 4-2. Round four becomes the first meeting between clubs Moturoa AFC and [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs]] FC. Wests winning 4-2 at New Plymouth. \n\n[[1969 Chatham Cup|1969]] - New Plymouth United are beaten 7-0. In round three Old Boys and Moturoa play out a 1 all draw. The match decided by corners and awarded to Moturoa. In round four Moturoa beat Wanganui Athletic 3-1 at Wanganui. Round five results in a 4-2 loss away to Palmerston City.\n\n1970 - A 2-0 loss to Old Boys ends this years cup. \n\n1971 - Round three, a 5-1 win versus NP United. In round four another drawn match against Old Boys, 1 all, won on corners by Moturoa. In round five Western Suburbs FC knock Moturoa out of the Chatham Cup 7-1 and go on to the title. \n\nThe heavy loss was avenged the next season, when Moturoa caused an upset, knocking the holders out of the cup with a fourth round 1-0 win. \n\n1972 - Moturoa beat Spotswood United 8-0 in round two and Old Boys 4-1 in round three. [[Gisborne City]] were drawn at home in round five, Western League champion Moturoa failed to find the back of the net against the mid-table [[New Zealand National Soccer League|National League]] side with four goals the difference. \n\n1973 - Moturoa United lose 2-0 to Old Boys in the Chatham Cup, the resources spread on a travelling Western League team, Central League team and an entry in the Air New Zealand National tournament. \n\n1974 - New Plymouth City were beaten 3-0 in round two. Stratford AFC were beaten 4-1 in round three. In round four Porirua United beat Moturoa 2-1 at New Plymouth.\n\n1975 - Moturoa United beaten by Central City in round two.\n\n1976 - The formation of the Taranaki Football Company produces the composite team Taranaki United. The team would play in the Central League third division and also enter the Chatham Cup. \n\nIn round one Moturoa AFC, now independent of New Plymouth United and a partner in the Taranaki Football Company, take a heavy 6-0 loss against the Taranaki United team.\n\n1977 - A round one fixture for Moturoa AFC against [[Opunake]] ends in a 2-2 stalemate. Penalties decide the tie with Opunake taking the honours 3-1.\n\n1978 - 5-0 victories, versus Waitara in round one and over Central City in round two. Round three Taranaki United were drawn and the tie was lost 3-0.\n\n1979 - First Chatham Cup match against Eltham AFC, a 4-2 win. In round two away fixture against Taranaki United results in a 3-2 loss.\n\nClubrooms and grounds at the Onuku Taipari Domain officially become new home for Moturoa AFC. \n\n1982 - Moturoa AFC amalgamate with Spotswood AFC. \n\n1980 to 1984 - Did not enter the Chatham Cup.\n\n1985 - A 3-1 round one victory at home against Wanganui City. In round two Palmerton North End were drawn away, the result a 3-1 defeat.\n\n1986 - Moturoa play Woodleigh Cosmos in round two at Onuku Taipari with 7-0 the score. In round three Masterton were drawn away, the result a 2-0 loss.\n\n1987 - In round two Wanganui East Athletic were beaten 3-2. In round three Wellington's Stokes Valley were beaten at home in the capital with a comprehensive 3-0 victory for Moturoa AFC. In round five National League club [[Napier City Rovers]] hosted at Onuku Taipari Domain, the match resulting in a 5-1 loss for Moturoa.\n\n1988 - Levin United are well beaten in round two at Moturoa 4-1. In round three the Hawkes Bay's [[Taradale, New Zealand|Taradale]] host Moturoa and win the match 3-0.\n\n1989 - Massey University travel to New Plymouth and snatch a 2-1 victory ending Moturoa City's challenge.\n\n1990 - Did not enter.\n\n1991 - Woodleigh Cosmos were beaten 1-0 at home. [[Lower Hutt City AFC|Lower Hutt City]] were drawn in round two with a 5-1 loss ending the cup for Moturoa.\n\n1992 - Did not enter.\n\n1993 - [[Red Sox Manawatu|Red Sox]] were played at Palmerston North in round two, the 2-1 result ending another spell competing for the Chatham Cup. Moturoa AFC would not enter again until 1999.\n\n1999 - [[Wellington United]] were beaten at [[Newtown Park]] in a 4-3 round two upset. In round three [[Paraparaumu United]] visited Onuku Taipari Domain and left as winners 4-2.\n\n2000 - [[Red Sox Riverside]] were destroyed 5-0 at home in round two, leading to a match with Wellington's [[Waterside Karori]]. The capital city team, third place in the Capital Premier League in 2000, were sent from the competition, a 2-1 win for Moturoa setting up a fourth round tie against [[Island Bay United]] in Wellington. After 120 minutes of play and no score the match went to penalties with Island Bay taking it 4-3.\n\n2001 - [[Wainuiomata AFC|Wainuiomata]] made the trip to New Plymouth for the round two match with Moturoa winning the game 2-1. In the away fixture in round three [[Wellington Olympic]] narrowly took the game 3-2.\n\n2002 - In the first Chatham Cup meeting between the two Taranaki clubs, Hawera FC were beaten 7-1 at New Plymouth. A replay from the third round of 1988 was drawn next with Moturoa again travelling to Taradale but this time returning victorious 3-1. [[Red Sox Manawatu|Manawatu]] were met in round four with the National League team handing out a 6-1 drubbing in Palmerston North.\n\n<br />\n\n==Central League==\n\nMoturoa was invited to join the provincial leagues in 1964.\n\nIn 1966 Moturoa played in the Western League for the Pearce Cup. Finishing third behind Thistle (Manawatu) and Kiwi United. \n\nThe decision to not compete for the Julian Cup this season marked the end of a seven year reign over the Taranaki championship beginning in 1959.\n\n1967 - The Wanganui clubs oppose the entry of Eastern Union (Gisborne) from the Eastern League to the Western League. All other clubs withdraw from the Western League and create the two division Central Districts League. Moturoa competes in the Premier Division with Eastern Union, Manawatu Thistle, Kiwi United, Napier Rovers and St. Andrews. A second Taranaki representative, Stratford AFC finished 8th in the ten team First Division. \n\nThe Taranaki-Wanganui League is won by an undefeated Moturoa who compete in both leagues, with Wanganui Athletic, Western Suburbs (Wanganui), New Plymouth United, Waitara, New Plymouth Old Boys and Wanganui United finishing in that order.\n\n1968 - The Central League begins.\n\nIn 1969 the club qualifies in the play-offs for the Central League with Masterton United, Upper Hutt United, Lower Hutt City, Napier City and Wanganui Athletic, though stays part of the Western League, its place taken by CYFC (Wellington).\n\n1970 - New Plymouth Old Boys win promotion to Central League. \n\n1971 - An undefeated Moturoa come second to Douglas Villa in the Central League playoffs. Two wins and three drawn matches against Central League teams, Wanganui City and Johnson Villa, and regional champions Brooklyn United and Napier City not giving enough points for promotion, even with a strike rate of 18 goals in 5 games.\n\nIn 1972 Moturoa won the Western Tasman League and promotion to Central League Division Two.\n\nNew Plymouth club United and Moturoa join and establish Moturoa United, giving the club(s) a Central League and Western League team.\n\nOn the 7th April 1973 the first match, an away game, in the Central League Division Two against home town rivals New Plymouth Old Boys, was played at Western Park, resulting in a 3-1 win for Moturoa United. Moturoa's team list for the inaugural Central League fixture: Paul Barratt, Don Harris, Ray Powell, Colin Selfe, Selwyn Brown, Peter Eliadis, Peter Wisnewski, Kevin Bussey, John Hunt, Geoff Collett, Robert Paul, Paul Brennan (sub for R. Paul).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Central League Soccer, ten year history of Central Regional Soccer League 1968-1977|last=Deverill|first=Victor, Charles|publisher=Wellington, Central Region|year=1978|isbn=|location=Puke Ariki, New Plymouth|pages=1\u2013175}}</ref>\n\nMoturoa United holds the honours of being the 1973 Central League Division Two champions.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1974 New Plymouth clubs Central City and Old Boys begin the New Plymouth City team. The team took the place of New Plymouth Old Boys in the second division of the Central League. Relegated from division two in 1974 and finishing third from bottom in 1975 the team folded into the Taranaki United entity in 1976 \n\nIn 1976, Moturoa joined the Taranaki Football Company entering into an arrangement to provide their top players to a composite team, [[Team Taranaki|Taranaki United]]. This agreement lasted until 1982 when the New Plymouth Old Boys club bought the Taranaki United identity and its position in the Central League as a limited company. The name Taranaki United was used until the end of the 1984 season.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1430.htm|title=Moturoa|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nCoached by Terry Brady, Moturoa were promoted back to the Central League as Taranaki and Western League champions in 1985.\n\nMoturoa entered the third division in 1986 and finished sixth with home town rivals New Plymouth City finishing 10th.\n\nIn 1987 Moturoa finished third. New Plymouth City won promotion behind Wainuiomata to the second division.\n\nIn 1988 Moturoa finished ninth from eleven teams with Port Hill United and Takaro beneath the club on the ladder. In the second division New Plymouth City also finished ninth.\n\nIn 1989 Moturoa and Central City/ New Plymouth City,<ref name=\"Central City\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1457.htm|title=Central City|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> formed a composite first team in the Central League called Moturoa/NP City. Moturoa relinquished the third division position with the new team taking the second division position held by City. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Central City\" /> \n\nThe playing strip in 1989 mixed the colours of both clubs, with the Pony branded shirt in red with gold shoulders, trim and numbering, with the main team sponsor, the Ngamotu Tavern across the chest in white.\n\nChatham Cup winner with [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs FC]] in 1971, John Connor was assigned the head coaching role. Three players were brought in for the 1989 season, Englishmen [[Russell Irving]] and Darren Fletcher along with New Zealand under 16 midfielder Karl Cherrie. The team won promotion to Division One as runners up to winners [[Havelock North Wanderers]]. Moturoa City had the best defence in the entire three divisions of the Central League in 1989 with only 16 goals conceded in 22 matches while scoring 42 goals.\n\nIn 1990 executive distractions off the pitch, travelling pressures, including an away match in the South Island, along with a significant change of squad saw the team relegated back to the second division.\n\nMoturoa independently retained the position in the Central League Division Two from 1991 following the failure of the two clubs to agree on the conditions of a proposed amalgamation.\n\nMoturoa was promoted to the [[Central Premier League]] for the 1994 season. After this season the club did not play in the Central League again until 2000 when it once again competed for the Central Premier League, having its final season to date at this level in 2003.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Taranaki Premier League Squad 2019==\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no= 1|pos=GK|nat=New Zealand         |name=Zane Coleman|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= |pos=  |nat=|name=|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 3|pos=  |nat=New Zealand         |name= Ethan Webber|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 4|pos=  |nat=New Zealand         |name= Corbin Richardson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 5|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Liam Scott|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 6|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Nathan Morath|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 7|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Jaden Taylor|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 8|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Troy Jury|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 9|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Hayden Murray|other=Captain}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|pos=     |nat=New Zealand|name= |other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=11 |pos=     |nat=New Zealand|name= Tyler Paterson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|pos=  |nat=New Zealand        |name= Ash Reader-Nokes|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Scott Manson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Jacob Crawford|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Zayed Rabbaney|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Sam Sutton|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Sam Westlake|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Nicholas Parthemore|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Dean Wilson|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Kayi Erol-Watt|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Kobi Hislop|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[:Category:Moturoa AFC players|Moturoa AFC players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Association football clubs in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Sport in New Plymouth]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Moturoa AFC\n| image = \n| fullname = Moturoa Association Football and Sports Club\n| nickname = \"the Reds\" - \"Roa\"\n| founded = 1928\n| ground = Onuku Taipari Domain, [[Moturoa]], [[New Plymouth]]\n| capacity = \n| chairman = Scott Manson\n| coach = \n| league = Taranaki Premier League\n| season = 2019\n| position = 1st\n| kit_alt1 = Red shirt with white collar, shorts and socks\n| pattern_b1 = _collarwhite\n| pattern_la1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_ra1 = _whiteshoulders\n| pattern_sh1 = _whitesides\n| pattern_so1 = _whitesides\n| leftarm1 = DD0022\n| body1 = DD0022\n| rightarm1 = DD0022\n| shorts1 = DD0022\n| socks1 = DD0022\n| kit_alt2 = Blue and white shirt, blue shorts and socks.\n| pattern_b2 = _blueshouldersandchest\n| pattern_la2 = _whitelower\n| pattern_ra2 = _whitelower\n| pattern_sh2 = _whitesides\n| pattern_so2 = _whitesides\n| leftarm2 = 0000BB\n| body2 = 0000BB\n| rightarm2 = 0000BB\n| shorts2 = 0000BB\n| socks2 = 0000BB\n| website = https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/\n}}\n'''Moturoa AFC''' is one of [[New Zealand]]'s oldest [[association football]] clubs. Based in [[New Plymouth]], the club traces its development back to the New Plymouth Watersiders team<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/70915|title=Watersides Soccer Team, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref> from the early years of the 20th century, and has historic  links to each of the many schools from the area and greater New Plymouth.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/80812|title=Motoroa Football Team|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nThe club refers to itself as the \"Traditional home of [[Taranaki Region|Taranaki]] football\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Moturoa AFC |url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/ |website=Moturoa AFC}}</ref> Its clubrooms and home ground are at the Onuku Taipari Domain, Ngamotu Road, New Plymouth.\n\nMoturoa AFC is home to many junior sides in the Taranaki age-group grades, providing a footballing base for players from the many surrounding schools.\n\nThe club also has three men's sides and two women's sides.\n\nThough not currently playing in the upper echelons of New Zealand football, Moturoa AFC has a rich history with the club having success in many regional and national competitions.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103150|title=Moturoa Association Football Club, 1960|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\n==2019 Season==\n\nThe Taranaki Premier League team are defending Taranaki Champions and have won three successive premierships in a row, completing the 2019 season unbeaten in the league and retaining the league challenge trophy.<ref name=\"website\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/|title=New Plymouth Moturoa AFC Football|website=moturoaafcnz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nThe team also hold the Sheffield United Plate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moturoaafc.co.nz/|title=New Plymouth {{!}} Moturoa AFC {{!}} Football|website=moturoaafcnz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> won in the pre-season by defeating the 2018 Central Federation Cup winners Eltham AFC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.centralfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/67908|title=A Men's Federation Cup final for the ages!|website=www.centralfootball.co.nz|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Moturoa Womens Premiership team are also defending Taranaki Champions, winning the league challenge trophy along with the Central Federation Cup and Duchess Cup titles.<ref name=\"website\" />\n\n==Early History==\n\nThe Watersiders won the Duff Rose Bowl in 1927 defeating Rangers (Fitzroy) in the final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19270815.2.33|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Both the Watersiders and related Wanderers team dissolved after this year.\n\nThe name Moturoa was first used with the Taranaki Football Association (TFA) for the 1928 season.<ref name=\"paperspast.natlib.govt.nz\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280611.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\nOne of the first TFA delegates representing Moturoa was Mr. J. McKay in 1928.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19290416.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> He had moved onto Caledonian by 1933 and in 1935 to New Plymouth Thistle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330426.2.69|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1928 - In early June in the Julian Cup, Caledonian inflict a heavy 4 - 0 defeat to Moturoa.<ref name=\"paperspast.natlib.govt.nz\"/> In late August Caledonian beat Moturoa again, this time in the Duff Cup, a huge score-line of 10 -0 recorded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280827.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> By early September results improved, still playing in the Duff Cup, Moturoa beat Rangers 3 - 0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19280910.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1929 - Moturoa's intermediate team, competing for the Plunket Cup, lost the final to Caledonian.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> The junior championship competition was keenly contested this year with many very promising players being found in the junior ranks, the game was said to have a very bright future in Taranaki. Moturoa made up for the Plunket Cup loss by winning the Plum Cup, the Chinese Cup and the Taranaki junior championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300408.2.51|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1930 - The TFA had a special meeting after receiving a letter from the New Plymouth clubs in the Northern Sub-Committee, with the Julian Cup lacking in entries. Only Stratford, Celtic (Hawera) and Albion had entered clubs. Moturoa, Caledonian, Rangers (Fitzroy) along with the club Pirates (New Plymouth) citing travel around Taranaki as detrimental to the progress of their junior competitions. A resolution was made by Mr. G.Littlejohn, that was met with approval by all the club representatives, except Rangers who had to consult their players. Moturoa's first game was scheduled for the 10th of May against Pirates,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300501.2.40|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> the result being a 5 - 1 win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300512.2.14|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> By the 19th of May, Rangers had dropped out for the season. Moturoa played Hawera team Celtic, losing 3 - 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300519.2.9|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>  Early June, Moturoa defaulted to Albion. Celtic, Pirates, Caledonian and Stratford managing to field teams.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300609.2.20|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> In early July Moturoa was drawn to play Stratford away in the first round of the Chinese Cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300703.2.8|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> A match day later, Stratford became the winners of the Chinese Cup for the season beating Hawera, with Moturoa facing Caledonian in a 4 - 4 draw for the Duff Cup (Duff Rose Bowl) the same weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300714.2.21|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> The attempt to win the years Priest Shield tournament was not successful. With two teams entered (A and B), Moturoa were losing semi-finalists to Caledonian after the match ended drawn and was decided by a corner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19300811.2.52|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1931 - In attendance at the TFA AGM were Moturoa club delegates, F. Roper and G. Rendell. The draw was made for the Julian Cup with Moturoa playing Albion in the first round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19310415.2.52|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Later in the year, Moturoa's senior team won the annual six-a-side competition for the Priest Shield at New Plymouth. There were six teams in the competition, which was conducted at Western Park. The players in the final for Moturoa were: R. Johns, R. and F. Roper, Anderson, White, Smith. And for Stratford: Grierson, Thomson, Henderson, O\u2019Shannessey, McGrory, Elgar. The final score was Moturoa 3  Stratford 1. White getting a hat-trick for Moturoa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19310914.2.68|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1932 - The season concluded with the annual Priest Shield contest at Western Park. Moturoa again exiting in the semi-finals, this year to Albion 2 - 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19320905.2.6|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n1933 - At the TFA's annual meeting in late April, held at Smith's Tea Rooms in Stratford, Waitara were accepted as an affiliated member of the association, giving further competition for Moturoa and the teams in the northern sub-committee. Albion were congratulated for winning all of the trophies in the prior season. A loan was made of \u00a35 to the northern sub-committee. Moturoa's delegates at the meeting were G.E. Roper and R.J. Page. Times had changed in South Taranaki, with the Stratford and two Hawera clubs listed as inactive. The season start date was set for May the 6th.<ref name=\":5\" /> Stratford turned this around and managed to field a team by May.<ref name=\":5\"/> The Julian Cup became a one-round competition. In all competitions except the Duff Cup, it was decided that the home team retained all the collections taken up at the match. A life sentence handed down to a player from an undisclosed club by the executive for the \"unfortunate breach of the rules of good conduct\", was reduced by the New Zealand Football Association (NZFA) to a five year suspension.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330426.2.69|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Moturoa played the newly affiliated Waitara for the first time in the middle of May. The match result being a draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330515.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The week after this significant fixture the club faced Caledonian losing 2 - 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330522.2.3|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Following that match another loss, this time to Albion 6 - 0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330529.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Moturoa played Stratford, at Stratford, in June in their final Julian Cup game for the season. The game ended in a one all draw, both goals from the first half. The Moturoa team list read as follows; Thompson, Roper, Simpson, Anderson, Bensley, Johns, White, Kenny, Christensen, a second Thompson and Grey. The Julian Cup was won again by Albion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330612.2.6|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> The first round of the Duff Rose Bowl saw Moturoa defeat the recent Julian Cup winners Albion, 2 - 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330626.2.5|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the second week of July the TFA suspended club football as the Taranaki representative team were travelling to Manawatu. An exhibition game of Probables v Possibles at Victoria Park used the remaining local players, with the hope of stimulating interest in the code again in South Taranaki. Moturoa's representatives scheduled to play in the fixture were, R. Kenny, R and F Roper, J. Thompson and A. Smith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330707.2.27|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nThe executive of the TFA met on the 11th of July at New Plymouth, Mr. G. E Roper from Moturoa agreed to broadcast talks on the game from local radio station 2XP. His first subject said to be \"The Organisation of Association Football in Schools\". At this time there was a considerable effort to establish the game in the schools. Stratford reporting that Tokaora and Waingongoro schools had requested balls. The executive considered the report of the referee, Mr. R. Swan, in regards to J. Thompson from Moturoa, and his sending from the field in the match against Waitara at [[Fitzroy, Taranaki|Fitzroy]] on July 1. Moturoa submitted a resolution and made representations in support, Thomson explained his view of the matter. It was decided to censure Thomson, but to take no further action as it was considered he had been sufficiently punished in being stood down from the Taranaki team that travelled to [[Manawatu District|Manawatu]] the match day prior. It was also noted in the minutes that Moturoa was to be asked to explain in \u201ccounting out\u201d the referee after a recent match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330712.2.61|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn bad weather in late July, Moturoa played Pirates in the Duff Rose Bowl. The score, unconfirmed, a possible 0 - 0 draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330724.2.4|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n1934 - Moturoa defeated Stratford away. Mr. Johns, a Moturoa supporter, stepping in for the referee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19330828.2.7|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Moturoa were runners up this year in the Julian Cup to winners Stratford AFC.\n\n1935 - Mr. Peter Gardner, who resided at Harbour Street, Moturoa, and Mr. E. Kenny were Moturoa's TFA delegates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/STEP19350417.2.45|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Gardner would later join New Plymouth Old Boys after WW2.\n\nMoturoa were one of the three New Plymouth sides in the Taranaki League for the Julian Cup in 1935, the other two being New Plymouth Albion and New Plymouth Thistle.\n\nIn 1938 the constitution of the club was first written.\n\n==Moturoa's Magyars==\n\nAttila Varga,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/obituaries/674894/Attila-Varga|title=Attila Varga|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> Lotsy Varga and Lotsy Polyanszky were prominent players for the club in the late 50s and 60s.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103151|title=Moturoa Soccer, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> All three players ended up being headhunted by Wellington-based [[Wellington United|Hungaria]]. Still considered by many to have been one of this country's best sides.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/obituaries/674894/Attila-Varga|title=Attila Varga|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/sport/105996458/hungarian-influence-remembered-as-wellington-united-marks-125th-anniversary|title=Hungarian influence remembered as Wellington United marks 125th anniversary|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nPolyanszky left Moturoa at the end of the successful 1960 season after being spotted playing for Moturoa against North Shore United in the Chatham Cup semi final at Blandford Park. In the 1961 season Polyanszky played in the Chatham Cup final for North Shore United. And eventually became player/coach of Hungaria by 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Small Price to Pay: Refugees from Hitler in New Zealand 1986\u201346|last=Beaglehole|first=Ann|date=1988|publisher=Bridget Williams Books|isbn=9780868616353|doi = 10.7810/9780868616353}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/photograph/3897/hungaria-association-football-club-1969|title=Hungaria Association Football Club, 1969|last=Taonga|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|website=teara.govt.nz|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> It has been said he was the most skillful footballer ever to grace a football field in New Zealand by many varied commentators of the game.\n\nHungaria played in the Central Region League before being invited to join the first [[New Zealand National Soccer League]] in 1970. It was the club's only season in the National League forming a composite team with Miramar Rangers as Wellington City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1524.htm|title=Wellington United|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973 Hungaria went solo again, this time in Division Two of the Central League, finishing second, to Moturoa United. Moturoa's hometown rivals Old Boys were also in Division Two in 1973.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZClubSoccer/id396.htm|title=1973|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> Moturoa drew with Hungaria at home 1 - 1, and lost away in Wellington 2 - 1, the close competition between the two teams shown in the almost equal statistics.<ref name=\":4\" /> Moturoa were promoted for the 1974 season as champions. Hungaria, as runners up had to wait another year in Division Two. The two clubs crossed over in 1974 with Moturoa being relegated back to Division Two and Hungaria taking their place in Division One.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZClubSoccer/id397.htm|title=1974|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==Chatham Cup==\n\nMoturoa has competed for the [[Chatham Cup]] since [[1949 Chatham Cup|1949]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/55223|title=Motorua [Moturoa], Soccer Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\n1949 - MAFC were beaten 6-1 at Western Park by [[Ohakea]].\n\n1950 - The club was drawn against the multi-national [[RNZAF]] team again suffering the same fate, though this time with the more respectable result of 5-4 at Ohakea. \n\nThe club shirt colour from this time was blue and white quarters with white shorts and black socks. \n\n1951 - The club goes into recess. Partially triggered from the effects of the [[1951 New Zealand waterfront dispute|waterfront dispute]] of this year on the wider [[Moturoa]] community.\n\n1953 - Life member, Hans Halder begins first of 25 years as MAFC President. Herb Hutton, life-member and first team player from 1945 to 1965, would resume the role of MAFC Secretary continuing until stepping down in 1972. \n\nThe club comes out of recess with a new shirt colour of red, with white shorts, and red and black hooped socks.\n\n1954 - Moturoa defeat [[Wanganui]] New Settlers 1-0  followed by a 4-2 win versus Palmerston North End, drawing a home game for the North Island quarter final and being soundly defeated 3-0 by Wellington's [[Stop Out]] at Western Park.\n\n1955 - [[Kiwi United]] knock Taranaki qualifiers New Plymouth Old Boys out in early August 5-2.\n\n1956 - Moturoa win the Taranaki Championship for the first time.\n\n[[Ted Meuli]] capped NZ test cricketer and NZ Universities football representative,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Salient12061949-t1-body-d28-d9.html|title=Soccer {{!}} NZETC|website=nzetc.victoria.ac.nz|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> begins to play for the club throughout this time<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/103150|title=Moturoa Association Football Club, 1960|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> after spending his prior years with New Plymouth rivals, Old Boys.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.pukeariki.com/objects/60097|title=Old Boys Soccer, Group|website=Puke Ariki Museum Libraries Tourist Information Taranaki New Zealand|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n1957 - An away game for Moturoa at the Sportsground against the Wanganui Settlers was lost 4-2. \n\n1958 - Stratford AFC qualify as Taranaki preliminary winners, knocked out by Kiwi United 3-2 at Western Park, New Plymouth.\n\n[[1959 Chatham Cup|1959]] - Moturoa beat Stratford at Western Park 4-1, starting one of the best cup runs in the clubs history. In the next round [[Wanganui Athletic]] were beaten 3-1 at [[Cooks Gardens]]. In the next round Napier Athletic travelled across to New Plymouth and were beaten 6-0 at Western Park. In the quarter final at the [[Basin Reserve]] in Wellington, Moturoa were beaten by [[Miramar Rangers]] 3-2.\n\n1960 - Moturoa win the first round 6-0 against Wanganui Settlers. In the next round Kiwi United were beaten 4-3. In the quarter final [[Brooklyn Northern United AFC|Northern]] were beaten 3-1 at Western Park.    \n\nIn the Chatham Cup semi final Moturoa travelled to Auckland to play [[North Shore United]] at [[Blandford Park]]. The match was lost 10-2, one of the heaviest losses in the clubs history.    \n\nThe 1960 season is one of most successful in the clubs history. Starting with the [[Kawerau|Kawerau Town]] pre-season tournament and ending with the club representing Taranaki and bringing home the Brown Shield for the first and only time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZRepSoccer/id1653.htm|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> by defeating Poverty Bay in the final of the tournament.     \n\nThe Brown Shield results from 1960 were, round one v Wanganui 6-1, round two v [[Manawatu]] 4-3, semi final v [[Bay of Plenty]] 3-1 and the final v Poverty Bay 2-1.    \n\nThe Brown Shield winning team of 1960 consisted of the players, G. Collett, A. Varga, G. Gregory (GK), H. Hutton, M. Fugett, T. Hawley, J. Marshall (captain), L. Varga, A. Evans, L. Polyanszky, T. Verbeet and coached by C. Wells.\u00a0 \u00a0\nThe Brown Shield originated in 1892. Taranaki first challenged for the shield in 1905, playing out a 1-1 draw against holders Wellington at New Plymouth on a Thursday in late September. C. Wilson scoring for Taranaki. The team made up with players from the Omata, New Plymouth and Waitara teams. In 1906 the next challenge was also without success, losing 4-0 to Wellington in a match played at [[Eltham]] in early September. The team made up with players from South Taranaki settlements [[Auroa]], [[Kaponga]], [[Hawera]] and Eltham.     \n\n1961 - Moturoa play New Plymouth City winning 4-0 at Western Park. In June, Wanganui Settlers were defeated 3-2 at the Oval in Wanganui. In July, Moturoa travelled to Napier, the match went to [[Napier Rovers]], the score unrecorded. \n\nOne of MAFC's best cup performances came in [[1962 Chatham Cup|1962]], with four home games at Western Park. In the Taranaki final Moturoa beat NP Old Boys 1-0. In the first round Wanganui Athletic were defeated 1-0. In the second round [[Red Sox Manawatu|St. Andrews]] were beaten 6-1. A quarter final with [[Seatoun AFC]] was won 3-1, leading to a semi-final against [[Hamilton Technical Old Boys]]. \n\nTechnical Old Boys won 4-0 in a match played before about 2000 people at [[Seddon Park]], Hamilton becoming the first North Island club outside of Auckland or Wellington to qualify for the final. Which spoke volumes for Moturoa, not only because they faced a Hamilton team with three [[List of New Zealand international footballers|New Zealand internationals]], but Technical proceeded to beat [[Otago]]\u2019s [[Northern AFC|Northern]] \u2013 who had won the [[1961 Chatham Cup|1961]] cup, 4-1 in the final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.melvilleunited.co.nz/semifinals-celebration/|title=Semifinals celebration|website=Melville United AFC|language=en-NZ|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n\n1963 - St. Andrews were beaten 5-2 at Western Park. At Wembley Park in the next match Wanganui United beat Moturoa 6-4.\n\nIn 1964 the club changes the playing kit colour to white shirts, red shorts and white socks. \n\nWanganui United were the opponent in round one, again at Wembley Park, a 6-2 defeat ended the cup for Moturoa.\n\nIn the [[1965 Chatham Cup|1965]] Chatham Cup, Moturoa were beaten in the 3rd round, 3-2 at [[Waitara, New Zealand|Waitara]]. \n\nWaitara had beaten [[Spotswood College|Spotswood]] 7-5 aet while Moturoa had beaten Old Boys 3-1 in the second round. Waitara would beat Wanganui United 3-1 in round four, and depart the competition in round five with a 2-0 loss to Napier Rovers. \n\nIn [[1966 Chatham Cup|1966]] MAFC begin wearing a full red playing kit for the first time.  \n\nIn round two of the Chatham Cup, Waitara were beaten 6-3. In round three, New Plymouth United were beaten 6-0. The next match saw the first fixture between Moturoa and [[Wairarapa United|Masterton Athletic]], a 5-2 victory. In round five Napier Rovers were beaten 4-2. In a replay of the 1959 quarter final Moturoa go out again at the hands of eventual winners of the 1966 cup. [[Miramar Rangers]] this time travelled to New Plymouth winning the tie 3-0 at Western Park. Its side featuring the country\u2019s leading goalkeeper at the time [[Peter Whiting (footballer)|Peter Whiting]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miramarrangers.co.nz/club-history|title=CLUB HISTORY|website=MIRAMAR RANGERS AFC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> \n\n1967 - Old Boys were beaten 3-0 in round one, New Plymouth United 6-3 in round two, in round three Napier Rovers defeat Moturoa 6-2 in Napier. \n\n1968 - In round three Moturoa beat Old Boys 4-2. Round four becomes the first meeting between clubs Moturoa AFC and [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs]] FC. Wests winning 4-2 at New Plymouth. \n\n[[1969 Chatham Cup|1969]] - New Plymouth United are beaten 7-0. In round three Old Boys and Moturoa play out a 1 all draw. The match decided by corners and awarded to Moturoa. In round four Moturoa beat Wanganui Athletic 3-1 at Wanganui. Round five results in a 4-2 loss away to Palmerston City.\n\n1970 - A 2-0 loss to Old Boys ends this years cup. \n\n1971 - Round three, a 5-1 win versus NP United. In round four another drawn match against Old Boys, 1 all, won on corners by Moturoa. In round five Western Suburbs FC knock Moturoa out of the Chatham Cup 7-1 and go on to the title. \n\nThe heavy loss was avenged the next season, when Moturoa caused an upset, knocking the holders out of the cup with a fourth round 1-0 win. \n\n1972 - Moturoa beat Spotswood United 8-0 in round two and Old Boys 4-1 in round three. [[Gisborne City]] were drawn at home in round five, Western League champion Moturoa failed to find the back of the net against the mid-table [[New Zealand National Soccer League|National League]] side with four goals the difference. \n\n1973 - Moturoa United lose 2-0 to Old Boys in the Chatham Cup, the resources spread on a travelling Western League team, Central League team and an entry in the Air New Zealand National tournament. \n\n1974 - New Plymouth City were beaten 3-0 in round two. Stratford AFC were beaten 4-1 in round three. In round four Porirua United beat Moturoa 2-1 at New Plymouth.\n\n1975 - Moturoa United beaten by Central City in round two.\n\n1976 - The formation of the Taranaki Football Company produces the composite team Taranaki United. The team would play in the Central League third division and also enter the Chatham Cup. \n\nIn round one Moturoa AFC, now independent of New Plymouth United and a partner in the Taranaki Football Company, take a heavy 6-0 loss against the Taranaki United team.\n\n1977 - A round one fixture for Moturoa AFC against [[Opunake]] ends in a 2-2 stalemate. Penalties decide the tie with Opunake taking the honours 3-1.\n\n1978 - 5-0 victories, versus Waitara in round one and over Central City in round two. Round three Taranaki United were drawn and the tie was lost 3-0.\n\n1979 - First Chatham Cup match against Eltham AFC, a 4-2 win. In round two away fixture against Taranaki United results in a 3-2 loss.\n\nClubrooms and grounds at the Onuku Taipari Domain officially become new home for Moturoa AFC. \n\n1982 - Moturoa AFC amalgamate with Spotswood AFC. \n\n1980 to 1984 - Did not enter the Chatham Cup.\n\n1985 - A 3-1 round one victory at home against Wanganui City. In round two Palmerton North End were drawn away, the result a 3-1 defeat.\n\n1986 - Moturoa play Woodleigh Cosmos in round two at Onuku Taipari with 7-0 the score. In round three Masterton were drawn away, the result a 2-0 loss.\n\n1987 - In round two Wanganui East Athletic were beaten 3-2. In round three Wellington's Stokes Valley were beaten at home in the capital with a comprehensive 3-0 victory for Moturoa AFC. In round five National League club [[Napier City Rovers]] hosted at Onuku Taipari Domain, the match resulting in a 5-1 loss for Moturoa.\n\n1988 - Levin United are well beaten in round two at Moturoa 4-1. In round three the Hawkes Bay's [[Taradale, New Zealand|Taradale]] host Moturoa and win the match 3-0.\n\n1989 - Massey University travel to New Plymouth and snatch a 2-1 victory ending Moturoa City's challenge.\n\n1990 - Did not enter.\n\n1991 - Woodleigh Cosmos were beaten 1-0 at home. [[Lower Hutt City AFC|Lower Hutt City]] were drawn in round two with a 5-1 loss ending the cup for Moturoa.\n\n1992 - Did not enter.\n\n1993 - [[Red Sox Manawatu|Red Sox]] were played at Palmerston North in round two, the 2-1 result ending another spell competing for the Chatham Cup. Moturoa AFC would not enter again until 1999.\n\n1999 - [[Wellington United]] were beaten at [[Newtown Park]] in a 4-3 round two upset. In round three [[Paraparaumu United]] visited Onuku Taipari Domain and left as winners 4-2.\n\n2000 - [[Red Sox Riverside]] were destroyed 5-0 at home in round two, leading to a match with Wellington's [[Waterside Karori]]. The capital city team, third place in the Capital Premier League in 2000, were sent from the competition, a 2-1 win for Moturoa setting up a fourth round tie against [[Island Bay United]] in Wellington. After 120 minutes of play and no score the match went to penalties with Island Bay taking it 4-3.\n\n2001 - [[Wainuiomata AFC|Wainuiomata]] made the trip to New Plymouth for the round two match with Moturoa winning the game 2-1. In the away fixture in round three [[Wellington Olympic]] narrowly took the game 3-2.\n\n2002 - In the first Chatham Cup meeting between the two Taranaki clubs, Hawera FC were beaten 7-1 at New Plymouth. A replay from the third round of 1988 was drawn next with Moturoa again travelling to Taradale but this time returning victorious 3-1. [[Red Sox Manawatu|Manawatu]] were met in round four with the National League team handing out a 6-1 drubbing in Palmerston North.\n\n<br />\n\n==Central League==\n\nMoturoa was invited to join the provincial leagues in 1964.\n\nIn 1966 Moturoa played in the Western League for the Pearce Cup. Finishing third behind Thistle (Manawatu) and Kiwi United. \n\nThe decision to not compete for the Julian Cup this season marked the end of a seven year reign over the Taranaki championship beginning in 1959.\n\n1967 - The Wanganui clubs oppose the entry of Eastern Union (Gisborne) from the Eastern League to the Western League. All other clubs withdraw from the Western League and create the two division Central Districts League. Moturoa competes in the Premier Division with Eastern Union, Manawatu Thistle, Kiwi United, Napier Rovers and St. Andrews. A second Taranaki representative, Stratford AFC finished 8th in the ten team First Division. \n\nThe Taranaki-Wanganui League is won by an undefeated Moturoa who compete in both leagues, with Wanganui Athletic, Western Suburbs (Wanganui), New Plymouth United, Waitara, New Plymouth Old Boys and Wanganui United finishing in that order.\n\n1968 - The Central League begins.\n\nIn 1969 the club qualifies in the play-offs for the Central League with Masterton United, Upper Hutt United, Lower Hutt City, Napier City and Wanganui Athletic, though stays part of the Western League, its place taken by CYFC (Wellington).\n\n1970 - New Plymouth Old Boys win promotion to Central League. \n\n1971 - An undefeated Moturoa come second to Douglas Villa in the Central League playoffs. Two wins and three drawn matches against Central League teams, Wanganui City and Johnson Villa, and regional champions Brooklyn United and Napier City not giving enough points for promotion, even with a strike rate of 18 goals in 5 games.\n\nIn 1972 Moturoa won the Western Tasman League and promotion to Central League Division Two.\n\nNew Plymouth club United and Moturoa join and establish Moturoa United, giving the club(s) a Central League and Western League team.\n\nOn the 7th April 1973 the first match, an away game, in the Central League Division Two against home town rivals New Plymouth Old Boys, was played at Western Park, resulting in a 3-1 win for Moturoa United. Moturoa's team list for the inaugural Central League fixture: Paul Barratt, Don Harris, Ray Powell, Colin Selfe, Selwyn Brown, Peter Eliadis, Peter Wisnewski, Kevin Bussey, John Hunt, Geoff Collett, Robert Paul, Paul Brennan (sub for R. Paul).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Central League Soccer, ten year history of Central Regional Soccer League 1968-1977|last=Deverill|first=Victor, Charles|publisher=Wellington, Central Region|year=1978|isbn=|location=Puke Ariki, New Plymouth|pages=1\u2013175}}</ref>\n\nMoturoa United holds the honours of being the 1973 Central League Division Two champions.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1974 New Plymouth clubs Central City and Old Boys begin the New Plymouth City team. The team took the place of New Plymouth Old Boys in the second division of the Central League. Relegated from division two in 1974 and finishing third from bottom in 1975 the team folded into the Taranaki United entity in 1976 \n\nIn 1976, Moturoa joined the Taranaki Football Company entering into an arrangement to provide their top players to a composite team, [[Team Taranaki|Taranaki United]]. This agreement lasted until 1982 when the New Plymouth Old Boys club bought the Taranaki United identity and its position in the Central League as a limited company. The name Taranaki United was used until the end of the 1984 season.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1430.htm|title=Moturoa|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nCoached by Terry Brady, Moturoa were promoted back to the Central League as Taranaki and Western League champions in 1985.\n\nMoturoa entered the third division in 1986 and finished sixth with home town rivals New Plymouth City finishing 10th.\n\nIn 1987 Moturoa finished third. New Plymouth City won promotion behind Wainuiomata to the second division.\n\nIn 1988 Moturoa finished ninth from eleven teams with Port Hill United and Takaro beneath the club on the ladder. In the second division New Plymouth City also finished ninth.\n\nIn 1989 Moturoa and Central City/ New Plymouth City,<ref name=\"Central City\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/Database/id1457.htm|title=Central City|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> formed a composite first team in the Central League called Moturoa/NP City. Moturoa relinquished the third division position with the new team taking the second division position held by City. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Central City\" /> \n\nThe playing strip in 1989 mixed the colours of both clubs, with the Pony branded shirt in red with gold shoulders, trim and numbering, with the main team sponsor, the Ngamotu Tavern across the chest in white.\n\nChatham Cup winner with [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs FC]] in 1971, John Connor was assigned the head coaching role. Three players were brought in for the 1989 season, Englishmen [[Russell Irving]] and Darren Fletcher along with New Zealand under 16 midfielder Karl Cherrie. The team won promotion to Division One as runners up to winners [[Havelock North Wanderers]]. Moturoa City had the best defence in the entire three divisions of the Central League in 1989 with only 16 goals conceded in 22 matches while scoring 42 goals.\n\nIn 1990 executive distractions off the pitch, travelling pressures, including an away match in the South Island, along with a significant change of squad saw the team relegated back to the second division.\n\nMoturoa independently retained the position in the Central League Division Two from 1991 following the failure of the two clubs to agree on the conditions of a proposed amalgamation.\n\nMoturoa was promoted to the [[Central Premier League]] for the 1994 season. After this season the club did not play in the Central League again until 2000 when it once again competed for the Central Premier League, having its final season to date at this level in 2003.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Taranaki Premier League Squad 2019==\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no= 1|pos=GK|nat=New Zealand         |name=Zane Coleman|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= |pos=  |nat=|name=|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 3|pos=  |nat=New Zealand         |name= Ethan Webber|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 4|pos=  |nat=New Zealand         |name= Corbin Richardson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 5|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Liam Scott|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 6|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Nathan Morath|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 7|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Jaden Taylor|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 8|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Troy Jury|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no= 9|pos=   |nat=New Zealand         |name= Hayden Murray|other=Captain}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|pos=     |nat=New Zealand|name= |other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=11 |pos=     |nat=New Zealand|name= Tyler Paterson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|pos=  |nat=New Zealand        |name= Ash Reader-Nokes|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Scott Manson|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Jacob Crawford|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Zayed Rabbaney|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Sam Sutton|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Sam Westlake|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|pos=|nat=New Zealand        |name= Nicholas Parthemore|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Dean Wilson|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Kayi Erol-Watt|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|pos=|nat=New Zealand|name= Kobi Hislop|other=Squad Player}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[:Category:Moturoa AFC players|Moturoa AFC players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Association football clubs in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Sport in New Plymouth]]\n", "name_user": "BG Onuku", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moturoa_AFC"}
{"title_page": "Solid Gold (pet food)", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=September 2007}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Solid Gold Pet, LLC\n| logo = <!-- [[File:Solid Gold Pet Logo.jpg|thumb|Solid Gold Pet Logo]] -->\n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation = [[El Cajon, California]] (1970s)\n| location = [[Chesterfield, MO]] [[United States]]\n| key_people = Julie- acting CEO & President,\nSissy Harrington-McGill\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| industry = [[Pet food]]\n| products = Dog food, Cat food, Supplements, Treats|\n| homepage = [http://www.solidgoldpet.com/ Premium Pet Food]\n}}\n'''Solid Gold Pet''' is a manufacturer and a worldwide supplier of natural, [[holistic]] [[pet]] foods based in Chesterfield, Missouri.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n== History ==\nThe founder of Solid Gold Pet, Sissy Harrington-McGill, raised [[great dane]]s. In the early 1970s she traveled to [[Germany]] to acquire [[dog]]s, which led to her developing her own pet food brand.\n\n== Recent==\nNow, over 40 years later, Solid Gold Pet specializes in the development of dry and wet dog and cat foods which contain no [[preservative]]s or [[saturated fat]]s, and are made of [[USDA]] Choice [[meat]]s such as bison, lamb and chicken, and [[grain]]s like whole grain brown [[rice]], [[barley]], [[oat]]s and [[millet]], instead of [[wheat]], [[soy]], or [[maize|corn]] like most other manufacturers. The company also has dog treats and supplements for both cats and dogs.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*http://www.solidgoldpet.com/\n*[https://www.petway.co.il/product-category/%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%AA%D7%92%D7%99%D7%9D/%D7%90%D7%A7%D7%A0%D7%94/ Acana Israel]\n\n[[Category:Cat food brands]]\n[[Category:Dog food brands]]\n[[Category:El Cajon, California]]\n\n\n{{food-product-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=September 2007}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Solid Gold Pet, LLC\n| logo = <!-- [[File:Solid Gold Pet Logo.jpg|thumb|Solid Gold Pet Logo]] -->\n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation = [[El Cajon, California]] (1970s)\n| location = [[Chesterfield, MO]] [[United States]]\n| key_people = Julie- acting CEO & President,\nSissy Harrington-McGill\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| industry = [[Pet food]]\n| products = Dog food, Cat food, Supplements, Treats|\n| homepage = [http://www.solidgoldpet.com/ Premium Pet Food]\n}}\n'''Solid Gold Pet''' is a manufacturer and a worldwide supplier of natural, [[holistic]] [[pet]] foods based in Chesterfield, Missouri.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n== History ==\nThe founder of Solid Gold Pet, Sissy Harrington-McGill, raised [[great dane]]s. In the early 1970s she traveled to [[Germany]] to acquire [[dog]]s, which led to her developing her own pet food brand.\n\n== Recent==\nNow, over 40 years later, Solid Gold Pet specializes in the development of dry and wet dog and cat foods which contain no [[preservative]]s or [[saturated fat]]s, and are made of [[USDA]] Choice [[meat]]s such as bison, lamb and chicken, and [[grain]]s like whole grain brown [[rice]], [[barley]], [[oat]]s and [[millet]], instead of [[wheat]], [[soy]], or [[maize|corn]] like most other manufacturers. The company also has dog treats and supplements for both cats and dogs.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*http://www.solidgoldpet.com/\n*[https://www.petway.co.il/product-category/%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%AA%D7%92%D7%99%D7%9D/%D7%90%D7%A7%D7%A0%D7%94/ Acana Israel]\n\n[[Category:Animal food manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Cat food brands]]\n[[Category:Dog food brands]]\n[[Category:El Cajon, California]]\n\n\n{{food-product-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GentlemanGhost", "label": "safe", "comment": "Articles generally should not be in both a category and a sub-category, seeWP:SUBCAT", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid_Gold_(pet_food)"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Dee Richards", "text_new": "{{Infobox serial killer\n| name=Stephen Dee Richards\n| image=StephenDeeRichards.jpg\n| caption= Illustration of Richards first published in the ''[[Nebraska State Journal]]'' in 1879\n| alias= Dick Richardson,{{sfn|ColumbusJournal|1878|p=2}} Samuel D. Richards,{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}}{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|Wilson|2014|p=11}} Stephen Lee Richards,{{sfn|Jenkins|2004|p=35}}{{sfn|Hedblom|Teeters|1967|p=202}}{{sfn|Newton|2006|p=317}} The Nebraska Fiend,{{sfn|SiousCityJournal|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|Jenkins|2004|p=35}} Kearney County Murderer\n| birth_date={{Birth date|1856|3|18}}\n| birth_place=[[Wheeling, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date={{Death date and age|1879|4|26|1856|3|18}}\n| death_place=[[Minden, Nebraska]], U.S.\n| cause=Execution by [[hanging]]\n| victims=6-9\n| country=[[United States]]\n| states=[[Iowa]], [[Nebraska]]\n| apprehended=December 24, 1878\n| penalty=Execution by [[hanging]]\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Dee Richards'''  (March 18, 1856 \u2013 April 26, 1879), also known in the media as the \"'''Nebraska Fiend,'''\" and the \"'''Kearney County Murderer'''\", was an American [[serial killer]] who confessed to committing six to nine murders in [[Nebraska]] and [[Iowa]] between 1876 and 1878.\n\nRichards was born in [[West Virginia]], though one source claimed that he was born in born in [[Ohio]], with his family moving around until settling in the [[Quakers|Quaker]] village of [[Mount Pleasant, Ohio]]. In 1876, Richards left his home in Mount Pleasant, heading Westward with the intention of 'seeking his fortune'. For a time, Richards found work at a local [[Sanatorium|asylum]], where he claimed to have lost all empathy towards others during his time there. In his later confessions, Richards claimed to have committed his first murder sometime in late 1876, two weeks after arriving in [[Kearney, Nebraska]]. After committing several other murders, in which he claimed was [[Murder in self defense|self-defense]], Richards later fled after the murder of the Harlson family, eventually being captured in his home town of Mount Pleasant. He was later tried and hanged in 1879, for the murder of Mrs. Harlson and her three children, and for the murder of his neighbor Peter Anderson.\n\nRichards later became known through an [[biography]], which was based on an interview conducted during his final arrest. The biography, which also included entries on other criminals of the time, was published [[posthumously]] in 1879, by the ''[[Nebraska State Journal]]''. Richards was later featured in an episode of [[SyFy Channel]]'s ''[[Paranormal Witness]]'', where his spirit was purported to have tormented a family.\n\n==Early and young adult life==\nStephen Dee Richards was born in [[Wheeling, West Virginia]],{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}{{refn|name=Note1|group=Note|In a biography published shortly after his execution, its author claimed that Richards was born in Ohio.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}}}} on March 18, 1856.{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} At the age of six, Richards moved with his family out of state to [[Ohio]], first settling in [[Monroe County, Ohio|Monroe county]], before later moving on to [[Noble County, Ohio|Noble County]].{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}}{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} At the age of eleven, his family moved once again, settling in the [[Quakers|Quaker]] village of [[Mount Pleasant, Ohio]]. Richards later described his mother as being a devout [[Methodist]], while claiming his father, a farmer,{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}} \"made no profession of religion\". During his residency in Mount Pleasant, Richards attended school, where he claimed that teachers there considered him well-behaved. At his mother's insistence, he also attended [[Sunday school]] and church regularly.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}}\n\nRichards would remain under his parents' roof during this time, working for farmers and other locals in the area. On September 16, 1871, Richards' mother passed away from unknown causes.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=11}}{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} Several years later, the age of 20, Richards met and became engaged to a young woman named Anna Millhorne, whom he kept regular correspondence with during his later travels up until his final arrest.  Also during this time, Richards came in contact with men of questionable occupation, and began passing around [[Counterfeiting of money|counterfeit bills]] that he claimed, had obtained through a man in [[New York City|New York]]. In February 1876, Richards left Mount Pleasant, heading west to \"seek his fortune\".{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=12}}\n\nFor a time, Richards set up residency in [[Iowa]], where he worked around as a farmhand at various local farms in [[Burlington, Iowa|Burlington]] and [[Morning Sun, Iowa|Morning Sun]]. He was later hired as an attendant at the [[Mount Pleasant Mental Health Institute|Iowa Lunatic Asylum]] in [[Mount Pleasant, Iowa|Mount Pleasant]], where his job was to bury dead patients. The ''New York Times'' reported that Richards \"had his finer senses blunted\" during his time at the asylum.{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=1}} In a quote in the ''Omaha Herald'', Richards reported claimed that his time working at the asylum made him lose much of his empathy for others:\n\"When I left there... I didn't care for anything and had no respect for human nature.\"{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}\n\nBy fall of 1876, Richards had left his job at the asylum and began drifting around the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]], finding intermittent work and occasionally consorting with [[Train robbery|train robbers]].{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} Eventually, he passed through [[Kansas City]] and [[Hastings, Nebraska]] before arriving in [[Kearney, Nebraska]].{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=15}}\n\n==Murders==\n===Early murders===\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1    = Dobytown, Nebraska 3.jpg\n| width1    = 295\n| alt1      = A photograph of a historical marker for Dobytown, Nebraska\n| image2    = Nebraska Sandhills NE97 Hooker County 3.JPG\n| width2    = 260\n| alt2      = A photograph of a prairie roadside in Sand Hills, Nebraska\n| footer = Newspaper records at the time reported that Richards confessed to have commited his first murder near [[Dobytown, Nebraska|Dobytown]] (left), or near [[Sandhills (Nebraska)|Sand Hills]] (right).\n}}\n\nIn a confession written after his final arrest, Richards confessed to having killed four men in 1876 and 1877 during his travels around Nebraska and Iowa.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|pp=10-11}}\n\nRichards claimed to have committed his first murder sometime in late 1876, two weeks after arriving in Kearney. According to his account, Richards met another man while traveling on horseback through the Nebraska countryside, and the pair soon decided to camp out for the night near [[Dobytown, Nebraska|Dobytown]],{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=13}} though several newspaper records have alternately reported that Richards had camped near [[Sandhills (Nebraska)|Sand Hills]].{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}{{sfn|StateJournal|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}  Settling down for the night, the two began gambling in a game of cards, with Richards winning most of the stranger's money. The following morning, as the two set off for Kearney, the stranger turned on Richards, demanding his money back. After refusing to return the man's money, Richards claimed that the man grew belligerent, resulting in Richards shooting him above the left eye, killing the man instantly. Confirming that the man was dead, Richards disposed of the body in the nearby river.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=13}}\n\nSeveral days later, while continuing towards Kearney, Richards encountered another stranger who was traveling on foot. The man told Richards that he had seen him in company with the stranger he had killed several days earlier and asked what had become of him;{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=13}}{{refn|name=Note2|group=Note|In his confession, Richards stated that the stranger had identified the murdered man as being named John, although he later admitted that he was unable to find out the man's last name.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}}}} in the course of the conversation, he realized that the two men were friends and business partners. Although he denied any knowledge of the other man, the stranger continued to hound Richards with questions.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}} Growing increasingly nervous from the stranger's interrogatory questions, Richards decided to kill the man to stop him from talking. Richards later stated that he waited until the stranger's back was turned, at which point he shot him in the back of the head, killing him. After disposing of the body, he later sold the stranger's horse in a nearby town before continuing on the road to Kearney. Before arriving at Kerney, Richards later stopped at the home of Jasper Harleson.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}} Jasper's wife Mary,{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} whom Richards described as being a \"free talker\", had noticed that his shirt was stained with blood and had asked him if he had been in a fight. Not realizing this, Richards jokingly replied that it must have come from the men he murdered, which ended the conversation.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}}\nTraveling to [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]], Richards used [[counterfeit money]] to purchase a horse and buggy from an unnamed man. Once Richards had left, the man soon discovered that the cash was counterfeit and tracked Richards down, demanding either good money or the return of his horse and buggy.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=15}} Richards initially refused, whereupon the man threatened to have him arrested. In response, Richards shot the man, burying his corpse before leaving the area.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=16}}\n\nIn March 1877, Richards left [[Grand Island, Nebraska]], on horseback with a young man with the last name of Gemge, heading to Kearney. Near the end of their journey, they camped for the night along the [[Platte River]] between [[Lowell, Nebraska|Lowell]] and Kearney. Richards woke at around 3 a.m. and aroused his partner, telling him that it was almost morning and that they ought to get back on the road; Gemge, infuriated at being woken so early, began arguing with Richards about the time. Richards tried explaining to Gemge that it was in fact 3 a.m., at which point Gemge began insulting him.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=17}} Richards later recounted what followed:\n\n{{Quote|text='It's a good thing you don't mean all you say,' I said. 'But I do mean it,\" he said. \"You don't want to mean it,' I said; and he picked up his revolver and saying, 'Here is something that backs all that I say,' cocked it. I looked at him, and thought, 'The fool acts as if he means to shoot,' and skipping out my little 33 I plugged him one in the head. That was the first trouble we had ever had.{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}}}\n\n===Murders of the Harlson family===\n[[File:Harlson Family Murders, Nebraska State Journal, December 1878.jpg|thumb|A newspaper clipping from 1878 reporting the Harlson Family murders.]]\nIn June 1878, while in Kearney, Richards was arrested and jailed for larceny,{{sfn|Wilson|2013|p=11}} which he later claimed was a \"false charge\". During his time in jail, he reunited with Mary Harlson, (In the transcription of Richards' confession, the name is spelled \"Harlson\".{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=19}} Other sources give alternate spellings, including \"Harrison\",{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} \"Harleson\",{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}} \"Haralson\"{{sfn|StateJournal|1878|p=2}} and \"Harrelson\"{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}). Jasper and another prisoner named Underwood had previously escaped from the Kearney jail, shortly before Richards\u2019 arrival. Mrs. Harlson had been jailed as well, on suspicion of aiding her husband during his escape.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} Richards and Mrs. Harlson agreed that she would sell him the deed to her property for $600, six months later.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=19}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}}\n\nAfter Richards was released from jail, he traveled around Nebraska for several months, doing business in Hastings, Bloomington and Grand Island, before arriving at the Harlson's Kearney County homestead on October 18, 1878. When Richards arrived, Mrs. Harlson transferred her property to him, and he settled down there for several weeks.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=20}} It was later reported by the ''[[New York Daily Herald]]'' that Richards had married Mrs. Harlson on November 2, in what they alleged was a scam in order to acquire ownership of Harlson's land.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}  A month later, Richards decided to kill Mrs. Harlson and her three children: ten-year-old Daisy, four-year-old Mabel, and two-year-old Jasper, nicknamed \"Jesse\" (Jasper Harlson was living in Texas at the time).{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} In his confession, Richards claimed that Mrs. Harlson 'talked too much', and had discovered that  he was guilty of murder: \"She would have 'given me away' had I let her live ... and so, knowing what she did, I thought it the safest plan to put her out of the way,\" he said.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=20}}\n\nOn November 3, 1878, Richards and another man named Brown, who had been staying at the house, got up early in the morning.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=20}} Brown went to feed the horses and do other chores around the farm after Brown had left, Richards found a [[spade]] and dug a hole near the house, he then snuck back into the house and murdered Mrs. Harlson, Daisy, Mabel and Jesse with an [[Axe murder|axe]].{{refn|name=Note3|group=Note|According to one report, Mrs. Harlson, and one of the other children were murdered with a [[Steam iron|smoothing iron]], while the others were physically assaulted.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}}} In Richards' confession, most of the Harlsons died immediately after the first several blows, with the exception of Daisy, whom he claimed had 'writhed in pain for some time' before dying.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|pp=21-22}} After the killings, Richards was said to have scrubbed away the bloodstains on the floor, and on his person, before sitting down for breakfast.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}} Afterward, he carried their bodies out of the house and buried them in the hole that he had made earlier. Later, when he was questioned about the Harlsons disappearance by several people, Richards claimed that they had left with Brown, and did not know when they would return.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=23}} A modern-day account would claim that Richards gave the excuse that Mary and her children had left to be reunited with her husband after she had transferred the deed of the farm to him.{{sfn|Wilson|2013|p=1+}} The bodies of Mrs. Harelson and her children were later discovered on December 11, with conflicting reports stating that they had been concealed underneath a haystack,{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}} rather than buried as Richards had later claimed.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=23}}\n\n===Murder of Peter Anderson===\nIn December 1878, Richards agreed to help his neighbor, a Swedish immigrant named Peter Anderson, with some work on Anderson's property.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=23}} An article for ''The Columbus Journal'', nine days after Anderson's murder, listed a certain Dick Richardson, a possible alias used by Richards while under Anderson's employment, as the one responsible for the murder.{{sfn|ColumbusJournal|1878|p=2}} On December 9,{{sfn|SiousCityJournal|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|Wilson|2013|p=11}} Anderson became ill after eating a meal Richards had prepared, causing him to suspect Richards had poisoned him. Anderson told a neighbor of his suspicions, then confronted Richards, the next day leading to a fight in which Richards beat Anderson to death with a hammer or hatchet.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=24}}{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} Alternate newspaper accounts reported that Richards had shot Anderson.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} Richards would later deny poisoning Anderson, saying using poison was not his style, and claimed that he killed in self-defense after Anderson attacked him with a knife.{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} Anderson's body was later discovered in the cellar of his house, buried underneath a pile of coal.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}\n\n==Fleeing the law==\nShortly after Anderson's murder, Richards decided to flee Kearny before the bodies would be discovered. However, a group of Anderson's neighbors approached Richards that evening in order to inquire about Anderson, whom they had not seen in a while. Arriving at the house, the group discovered Richards hitching up Anderson's horses, and when questioned about Anderson's whereabouts Richards reportedly distracted the group, claiming that Anderson was inside. As the neighbors entered the house, Richards fled the scene on horseback to [[Bloomington, Nebraska|Bloomington]].{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}}\n\nFleeing the area, Richards traveled east, alternating between horse, train, and foot, passing through Omaha, Chicago, (an article from the ''[[Lincoln Journal Star]]'' alternately claimed that Richards, under the alias Samuel Richards, had instead fled to [[Red Cloud, Nebraska|Red Cloud]] after the murder through Hastings, Chicago).{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}} While on the run, he met up with Jasper Harlson, the ex-husband of Mrs. Harlson, and Underwood, traveling with them through [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], and [[Bridgeport, Ohio]] before reaching his hometown of [[Mount Pleasant, Ohio]].{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} Nebraska state Governor [[Silas Garber]] issued an arrest warrant for Richards on December 16, 1878, with the reward of $200 (about $5,173.56 in 2020) for his arrest and conviction.{{sfn|NSHistoricalSociety|1942|p=501}}\n\n===Capture===\nThe circumstances and location of Richards' eventual arrest have varied somewhat, with some newspaper records around that time reporting that Richards was arrested shortly after his arrival in Mount Pleasant.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|Murdock|1879|p=2}} ''[[The Wheeling Daily Intelligencer]]'' reported that, upon arriving in a town near Mount Pleasant, Richards was subsequently identified by an old acquaintance, who detained him with the help of a colleague.{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} Most records at the time have listed the date of Richards' arrest as being December 24, 1878.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} Though one contemporary source has claimed that Richards was arrested in [[Austin, Texas]] in early 1879,{{sfn|Ramsland|2006|p=4}}\n\nRichards himself would later claim to have nearly evaded capture in Ohio, stating that he had intended to travel back to Nebraska, as he reasoned it would have been the last place anyone would have bothered to look. Richards also reported a different story of the circumstances of his arrest. In his account, sometime after arriving in his hometown in Jefferson County, he had attended a [[ballroom dance]] with two unidentified women. While strolling just outside of town, with the women in attendance, he claimed to have spotted what appeared to be several officers approaching him. Wanting to fight his way out, Richards told his companions to head back to town to which they refused, and as the officers confronted them, Richards surrendered.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} Richards would later state that, if the women had left, he would not have been arrested:{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}}\n\n{{Quote|text=\"If I hadn't had the two girls with me, I guess the constable, McGrew, who arrested me, would have been a dead man - either of us would, for I'd have shot.\"}}\n\nAfter his arrest, Ohio authorities jailed him in [[Steubenville, Ohio|Steubenville]], where he wrote two articles for the local newspaper, confessing to a total of nine murders{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}{{refn|name=Note4|group=Note|Some newspaper accounts have alternately reported that Richards had confessed to six murders, rather than nine.{{sfn|Murdock|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}}} over a period of three years.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} Sheriff David Anderson of [[Buffalo County, Nebraska|Buffalo County]] and Sheriff Martin of [[Kearney County, Nebraska|Kearney County]],{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} (an alternate record listed both Anderson and a Simon C. Ayer as the arresting officers){{sfn|NebraskaSenateJournal|1879|pp=501}} who had pursued Richards all the way from Nebraska to Ohio, later returned with him to Nebraska.{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} [[Leavenworth, Kansas]] newspaper ''The Workingman's Friend'' reported that the Chicago authorities received a portion of the $200 reward.{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}  At the time of his arrest, authorities suspected that Richards was a member or leader of a gang of outlaws that plagued the state,{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} a sentiment that was not shared by ''[[The Nebraska State Journal]]''.{{sfn|StateJournal|1878|p=2}} Public outrage towards Richards near the areas where his crimes were committed were said to be so intense that both Anderson and Martin{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}} feared that Richards would be [[Lynching|lynched]] by the outraged townsfolk. As a result, authorities came to the decision that Richards was not to be transferred into any of those areas.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}} Shortly before his trial, Richards voiced his suspicions that he would be convicted and hanged for his crimes.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}\n\n==Trial==\nRichards' trial began on January 16, 1879, in [[Minden, Nebraska]], with Judge Gaslin presiding over the court proceedings. With the charges of [[murder in the first degree]], Richards pled [[Not guilty plea|not guilty]], arguing  that Anderson's murder was in self-defense, and therefore justifiable.{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} After two hours of deliberation,{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} Richards was found guilty of murder and sentenced to death by hanging,{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} with the date for his execution set for April 26, later that year.{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}\n\n===Execution===\nUpon his return to Nebraska, The ''Omaha Herald'' reported: \"Richards manifested supreme indifference to his lot, was perfectly willing to be brought direct to Kearney Junction and said he had as soon died one way as another.\"{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}} Shortly after Richards' trial, Sheriff Martin announced that the execution would be open to the public, though he was afraid that the large crowd of onlookers would be roused to violence.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879a|p=4}} Stephen Dee Richards was hanged in Minden on April 26,{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} 1879.{{sfn|Newton|2006|p=399}} A crowd of approximately 25,000 was said to be in attendance to witness the hanging, and, at precisely 1 pm, Richards was led to the gallows by Sheriff Martin and his deputy. In his final words, Richards launched into an impassioned defense for his actions, again claiming that Anderson's death was in self-defense, while also claiming that he had nothing to do with the murder of the Harlson family. Richards then stated that he \"had faith in Christ\", and pleaded with the crowd to sing with him the hymn ''[[Come Thou Fount of Every Blessing]]''. At precisely 1:17 pm, Richards was hanged from the gallows, with the attending reporter for the ''[[St. Louis Globe-Democrat]]'' stating that it took fifteen minutes for the criminal to die.{{sfn|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}}\n\nAfterwards, his body was buried in a nearby grave,{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}} which was later dug up and his bones scattered in the streets of Kearney.{{sfn|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}} In 1882, it was reported that ''Kearney County Gazette'' had obtained Richards' skull and had placed it on display,{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}} the current location of the skull remains unknown.\n\n==Pathology==\n{{Quote box|width= 40%|align=right|quote=\"I have killed nine persons, and I can't say I feel any worse for it.\"{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}}|source = Richards, describing his lack of guilt over his crimes}}\n\nAt the time of Richards' killing spree and execution, [[criminal psychology]] and [[Criminal profiling|profiling]] had not yet become a recognized field of study, having first been utilized during the [[Jack the Ripper|Jack the Ripper murders]] in 1888, nine years after Richards' execution.{{sfn|Bonn|2017}} Richards was observed by many to have displayed a complete lack of remorse towards his crimes, after his arrest.{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} An article in the ''[[New York Daily Herald]]'' reported of Richards' mood after his capture as being 'carefree and cheerful'.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}}{{sfn|Murdock|1879|p=2}} Members of the press that interviewed Richards after his arrest were struck by his calm and collected behavior.{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}} During an interview with a reporter from the ''Wheeling Daily Intelligencer'', Richards himself stated that he knew that he would be executed for his crimes, but also stated that he was unafraid of death and was \"ready to meet it\".{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=1}} When his death sentence was announced by the jury, Richards mood was said to have been cheerful after the verdict.{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} In a report for the ''St. Louis Globe-Democrat'', who also expressed doubt over the number of murders Richards claimed to have committed, was said to have broken down during his final moments.{{sfn|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}}\n\nConsidered reasonably handsome by observers, Richards was described by reporters at the time of his arrest as being \"heavily built\", standing approximately six feet tall, with dark hair and blue eyes.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}\n\n==Legacy==\nBefore his execution in 1879, Richards was interviewed by the Nebraska [[State Journal]]. The interview was later published after Richards' execution on May 1, 1879, under the title ''Life and Confession of Stephen Dee Richards, the Murderer of Nine Persons Executed at Minden, Nebraska, April 26, 1879''. The book would also include entries of other criminal cases at the time.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=72}}{{sfn|McDade|1961|p=239}} A detailed analysis of Richards' was later published by J. Sanderson Christianson titled ''The Philosophy of Insanity: Richard, the Nebraska Fiend''.{{sfn|Bell|1885|p=668}}\n\nRichards was also featured in an episode of [[SyFy Channel]]'s ''[[Paranormal Witness]]'', in an episode titled \"The Nebraska Fiend\" where a family was reportedly tormented by the killer's [[spirit]].{{sfn|MTTG 2016}}{{snf|Enk|2016}}{{sfn|SyfyChannel|2016}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Bell|first1=Clark|title=The Medico-Legal Journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T7RXAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA668|volume=49|year=1885|publisher=Medico-Legal Society}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Jenkins|2004|p=39}}|author=Philip Jenkins|title=Moral Panic: Changing Concepts of the Child Molester in Modern America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g_wT9QQgu1IC&pg=PA35|date=December 2004|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-10963-4}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=McDade|first=Thomas|title=The annals of murder: a bibliography of books and pamphlets on American murders from colonial times to 1900|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=98s-AAAAIAAJ|year=1961|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Newton|2006|p=117}}|author=Michael Newton|title=The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DwNVbOcTncwC&pg=PA117|date=February 2006|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-6987-3}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|NSHistoricalSociety|1942|p=501}}|editor=John Lewis|title=Messages and Proclamations of the Governors of Nebraska, 1854-1941|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HxpSAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA501|volume=1|year=1942|publisher=Nebraska State Historical Society}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Ramsland|2006|p=4}}|author=Katherine M. Ramsland|title=Inside the Minds of Serial Killers: Why They Kill|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qbppiQQw4DkC&pg=PA4|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-99099-2}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|StateJournal|1879b|pp=1-72}}|author=Anon.|title=Life and Confession of Stephen Dee Richards: The Murderer of Nine Persons, Executed at Minden, Nebraska, April 26, 1878|date=May 1, 1879|publisher=State Journal Co.|location=Lincoln, Nebraska}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|NebraskaSenateJournal|1879|pp=501}}|author=Nebraska Senate Legislature|title=Senate Journal of the Legislature of the State of Nebraska: Fifteenth Regular Session|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5edKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA521|volume=15|year=1879|publisher=Journal Company, State Printers}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Hedblom|Teeters|1967|p=202}}|author1=Negley King Teeters|author2=Jack H. Hedblom|title=\"... Hang by the neck ...\": the legal use of scaffold and noose, gibbet, stake, and firing squad from colonial times to the present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fFNCAAAAIAAJ|year=1967|publisher=C. C. Thomas}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Wilson|2014|pp=11-13}}|author=R. Michael Wilson|title=Legal Executions in Nebraska, Kansas and Oklahoma Including the Indian Territory: A Comprehensive Registry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XEKou1ogxpoC&pg=PA11|date=January 10, 2014|publisher=McFarland & Company|isbn=978-0-7864-8909-1}}\n{{colend}}\n\n===Websites===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Richards, the Kearney County Murderer, Gives for the First Time Full Details of His Crimes|newspaper=The [[Omaha Herald]]|date=December 31, 1878|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|OmahaHerald 1878}}}} \n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Watching for a Wholesale Murderer |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37185412/stephen_dee_richards_new_york_daily/|accessdate=October 15, 2019|publisher=New York Daily Herald|date=December 14, 1878|location=New York, New York|page=7|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The Journal |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48359469/peter-anderson-murdered-stephen-d/|accessdate=April 11, 2020|publisher=The Columbus Journal|date=December 18, 1878|location=Columbus, Nebraska|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|ColumbusJournal|1878|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=A Vile Murderer: A Prisoner Confesses to Having Murdered Nine Persons Over Three Years|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37226867/stephen_d_richards_new_york_daily/|accessdate=October 30, 2019|agency=The New York Daily Herald|date=December 25, 1878|